<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lightning Sparks Apartment Fire in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Fires believed to have been
sparked by lightning gutted more than 100 apartments in the
Atlanta area in Georgia State in southeast United States Tuesday
night, said reports reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A fire that began on the roof of one building of the Post
Terrace Apartments north of Atlanta destroyed 56 units. The fire
quickly worked its way down the four-story structure until it
consumed the entire building.
</P>
<P>
Firewalls helped keep the blaze from spreading to other
buildings in the 296-unit complex, the reports quoted Fulton
County Police Terry Mulkey as saying.
</P>
<P>
No injuries were reported. At least 60 residents were forced to
spend the night at a nearby hotel.
</P>
<P>
A band of powerful thunderstorms was believed to have sparked
the blaze and other less severe fires throughout the area.
Lightning lit up the sky throughout the city as sheets of water
poured down on motorists during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
Fires also destroyed 16 units of an apartment building and
damaged 16 more in another building. Twelve units were destroyed
in a fire at a fourth apartment complex. Several houses also
caught fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
