<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday met in a closed-door session to discuss a report,
presented by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan last Friday, on the
latest development of the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled meeting came one day after Libya demanded an
immediate lifting of the U.N. sanctions, imposed in 1992 and
toughed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Libyan Permanent Representative to the United Nations Abuzed
Omar Dorda said in his nine-page letter to the Security Council
Tuesday, "The politicization of this legal dispute, in whatever
form or by anyone, is not acceptable."
</P>
<P>
Before walking into the Security Council chamber, the Libyan
ambassador told reporters the sanctions "should be lifted, because
Libya really met all its obligations that were in the Security
Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
"So, there is no more reason at all to delay the lifting," he
said, "If there is anyone who has his own interests" in connection
with the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner over the Scottish town
of Lockerbie, Libya would like to solve the problem bilaterally
through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his report that Libya had promised to cooperate
with a trial of the two suspects and pay compensation if the two
suspects, handed over on April 5 for trial before a Scottish court
in the Netherlands, were convicted.
</P>
<P>
But the U.N. chief said that the United States needed more
evidence before it would agree to lifting the sanctions, mainly
because the trial of the two suspects will not start before
February 2000.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, which include an air and arms embargo and a ban
on oil equipment, were suspended on April 5, when Tripoli
surrendered for trial before the Scottish court in the
Netherlands. The two Libyans were accused of planting a bomb on
Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie. A total of 270 people were
killed in the explosion, 189 of them were Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
