<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Constitutional Commission Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Zimbabwean
Constitutional Commission Godfrey Chidyausiku said Wednesday that
the views of all Zimbabweans will be contained in the final report
on constitution reform.
</P>
<P>
"The commission is above partisan politics," he told a press
conference in Zimbabwean capital Harare.
</P>
<P>
"We aim at bringing a democratic constitution by ensuring that
all the people of this country are heard," said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
"There is no hidden agenda and there are no interfering
fingers, political or other kind from any authority or quarter,"
he said. "Everything we are doing is above board and will continue
to be so until we complete the historic task before us."
</P>
<P>
Chidyausiku said the commission is driven by national interests
and not views of a few vocal groups.
</P>
<P>
The chairman emphasized the need for people to understand that
the commission is not a review body because they are drafting
totally new law.
</P>
<P>
The commission's mandate is to collect people's views and make
recommendations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to donors to provide financial assistance to enable
the commission to carry out its mission without hurdles.
</P>
<P>
The commission requires 600 million Zimbabwean dollars (15
million U.S. dollars) for its work which would last until November
30, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
