<HEADLINE> Death Penalty of Rwanda Genocide Suspect Repelled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Court of Appeals in southwest
Rwanda has acquitted a former government official who had been
sentenced to death by the criminal court last year, the Rwanda
News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Theodore Munyengabe, 41, had been found guilty of eight counts
of genocide and crimes he perpetrated in the April-July 1994 in
spearheading the mass killings of about 50,000 minority ethnic
Tutsis who had sought refugee at various local Catholic churches
and the soccer stadium.
</P>
<P>
The court was quoted as arguing that Munyengabe did not have
any defense counsel during the trial, and therefore repelled the
death penalty sentence.
</P>
<P>
Munyengabe's acquittal was the second of that kind after the
Kigali's Appeals Court acquitted a Burundi citizen, Leonidas
Ndikumana, who had been sentenced to death for his involvement in
the killings of Tutsis and moderate Hutus in Gikondo suburb of
capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Since their opening in December in 1996, Rwandan criminal
courts tried over 1,500 genocide suspects, among whom over 300
were sentenced to death, and over 400 to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two genocide culprits were publicly executed around the
country last April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Asks Pakistan to Withdraw Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian caretaker Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee said Wednesday that India would watch for the
results of Pakistan's intention to withdraw from the Indian side
of the Line of Control (LOC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference of chief ministers here, Vajpayee said,
"We are informed that Pakistan has agreed to withdraw. We will
watch for results on the grounds. In the meantime our operations
shall continue unabated."
</P>
<P>
India launched a big military operation in early May to "flush
out Pakistan-backed infiltrators" from the Indian side of the LOC"
and the fighting is still going on in the Kargil sector of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Media reports on Sunday said U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in their talks reached an
agreement and Pakistan promised to withdraw its troops.
</P>
<P>
The chief ministers were briefed on the current situation in
Kargil by the chiefs of the armed forces, Defense Minister George
Fernandes, Home Minister L. K. Advani and Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee allayed concerns expressed by political parties that
the government had accepted third-party mediation on Kargil,
saying India had made it clear that "there is no room for
third-party involvement, however well-intentioned."
</P>
<P>
He said India had been in close touch with the international
community to give diplomacy a chance to enable New Delhi to
achieve the objective of complete and unconditional withdrawal of
the Pakistan forces. This was not internalization of the Kashmir
question, he added.
</P>
<P>
After expressing satisfaction over the reaction of the
international community, Vajpayee said, "No outsider owes it to us
to reverse the present incursions. We alone are responsible for
safeguarding our security and protecting our interests. While we
are grateful for the support and understanding of the
international community, there will be no compromise on our
military operations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
