<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Rules Out Leadership Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Wednesday dismissed speculations by some sections of the media
that there was a leadership crisis following the death of
Vice-President Joshua Nkomo.
</P>
<P>
"There is no crisis at all and I do not think the issue is a
controversial one," he told journalists in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration that the country's constitution was
to be reviewed and the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union
(Patriotic Front) Congress would meet in December this year, there
was no hurry in trying to determine who was going to replace
Nkomo, said the president.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the Congress to decide the way forward on the
issue of succession and also taking note of the changes that may
come after the constitutional review," the Zimbabwe News Agency
quoted Mugabe as saying.
</P>
<P>
There is a provision in the Zimbabwean constitution that there
should be two vice-presidents.
</P>
<P>
Following the death of Nkomo there is only Simon Muzenda as
Vice- President.
</P>
<P>
There have been numerous media reports about a leadership
crisis within the ruling party following the death of Nkomo last
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: Popular Iranian Moderate Daily Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran's most popular moderate daily
Salam (Hello) was closed down on Wednesday by Iranian
conservative-dominated judiciary, the Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that the closure decree was announced by
the judiciary through telephone call to the daily, which has
strongly supported President Mohammad Khatami since his election
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The closure came one day after Salam reported in its front
page that Saeed Emami (also famous as Islami), one of the main
agents behind serial political killings in the country, has
proposed to amend the country's press law in order to control the
press.
</P>
<P>
Salam said that Emami, former deputy intelligence minister for
security affairs, sent a letter last October to then intelligence
minister, calling on the ministry to raise proposals to amend the
press law.
</P>
<P>
Emami, who was arrested for masterminding killings of several
Iranian dissidents, committed suicide in prison on June 19 by
taking depilatory substance while taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Iran Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his wife
were stabbed to death at home while at least three dissident
writers were mysteriously killed in Tehran later last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star Shuttlers Make No Mistake in Thailand Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- All star shuttlers stormed into the
third round after matches on the second day of the World Grand
Prix Thailand Open Badminton Championships on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jun of China, top seed of the men's singles, beat his
Singaporean rival comfortably 15-6, 15-2, while his compatriot Dai
Yun, women's top seed, also proved too strong for local shuttler
Orathai Lapleungthong with a 11-1, 11-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese saw only two losses on Wednesday from Luo Yigang in
the men's singles and Yao Jie in the women's.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Tian Bingyi said Luo, who is suffering belly
injury, lost 4-15, 14-15 to joint 3/4 seed Rachid Sidek of
Malaysia, whom he just beat in the Malaysia Open a week ago.
</P>
<P>
But Yao's defeat could only be attributed to her unsatisfactory
performance, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
Fung Permadi of Chinese Taipei, second seed for men's singles,
also entered the next round.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Peter Gade-Christensen, who took part in the only
men's doubles event, also promoted to the next round with his
partner.
</P>
<P>
The six-day 80,000-U.S. dollar badminton competition has drawn
nearly 300 players from 19 countries and regions, including China,
Indonesia, Malaysia and Denmark, vying for the prize money and
world rankings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
