<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya to Resume Normal Ties With Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Libyan diplomat
said here Wednesday that Tripoli will soon resume normal relations
with Britain and it was time for the United Nations to lift
sanctions against his country.
</P>
<P>
Abuzed Omar Dorda, the Libyan permanent representative to the
United Nations, told reporters that a resumption of ties with
Britain, announced by British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook. "is
the natural thing."
</P>
<P>
"Libya did not cut relations with any country. We will have
normal relations with Britain and we will establish diplomatic
relations soon," said the Libyan ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Dorda made the remarks in response to Cook's Wednesday
announcement that London was resuming diplomatic relations with
Libya after Tripoli agreed to cooperate in police investigation
into the 1984 shooting of a British policewoman outside the Libyan
Embassy in London.
</P>
<P>
Cook told parliament that Libya had also agreed to pay
compensation for the killing in the bombing of a Pan Am airliner
over the Scottish town of Lockerbie in December 1988 after the two
Libyan suspects are convicted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dorda said that the sanctions should be lifted
permanently because "Libya really met all its obligations towards
Security Council resolutions so there is no more reason at all to
delay the lifting."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when the U.N. Security Council is meeting
in a closed-door session to discuss a report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who said in the report last Friday
that Libya had complied with many of the 15-nation Council's
demands but that he was unable to make a recommendation on lifting
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Britain ended its diplomatic relations in 1984 after a
policewoman was shot outside the Libyan Embassy in London, but
British officials have met Libyan envoys many times since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Unsatisfied with Barak's Peace Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Wednesday expressed
unsatisfaction with the remarks made by Israel's newly-elected
Prime Minister Ehud Barak about reviving the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"Why didn't Barak mention the United Nations Resolution 425
when he talked about his intention to withdraw Israeli forces out
of Lebanon?" said Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss when meeting
with local visitors.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to be so pessimistic when many people are
showing optimism toward the reactivation of the peace talks in
the region," Hoss added.
</P>
<P>
Addressing to parliament before being sworn in on Tuesday,
Barak said his government intends to withdraw Israeli forces out
of Lebanon and make peace with all Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
to oust Israeli forces and its proxy militia South Lebanon
Army out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Last year, former Israeli government of Benjamin Netanyahu,
who was blamed for the stalemate in the peace process during his
three-year tenure, adopted Resolution 425 which calls on
Israel to withdraw it troops from south Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
However, it linked the pullout with security guarantees made by
the Lebanese government in a bid to protect its north against
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, a main power broker in Lebanon, rejected
the offer, demanding the Jewish state to implement the resolution
without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Hoss stressed that Lebanon will continue to be committed to
achieving just and comprehensive peace in the region and will
insist that talks restart from where they broke off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
