<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Bonds Stand Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South African bonds Wednesday
continued to hover around the 14-percent level, but appear to be
finding it tough to break through this key level.
</P>
<P>
The yield on the benchmark 150 rand (25 U.S. dollars) bond
ended at 14. 080 percent after the 50 basis point rate cut
announcement by Standard Bank had raised hopes of breaching the
key 14-percent level after a best level of 14 percent was tested
at midday. It was at 14.160 percent at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said bonds had already discounted the interest rate cut
and the fact that the Dow Jones had started on a negative footing
spoiled the prospects of breaking 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank Wednesday announced a 50 basis point interest
rate cut to 17.5 percent with effect from July 14.
</P>
<P>
The short-term interest rates have been lending support on the
bond market.
</P>
<P>
If the global markets close average in relation to the Dow
Jones, Emerging Market Bond Index and other indicators, South
African bonds stand a great chance to remain firm, market
observers said.
</P>
<P>
The rand was last at 6.05 rand per dollar from 6.0350 at the
previous close and a best level of 5.9790 Tuesday, while equities
were struggling to go firmer Wednesday on the gold slump. 
</P>
</TEXT>
