<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Agencies Begin Work on Environment in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (xinhua) -- Two U.N.agencies have established
working relationships with the principal U.N. authorities and the
NATO-led peace- keeping mission in Kosovo (K-FOR) leadership, in
order to share information and coordinate activities related to
environment and human settlements in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Environmental Program (UNEP) and the U.N. Center for
Human settlements (Habitat) jointly established the Balkans Task
Force (BTF) in May to look at the direct environmental and human
settlements impacts of the conflict in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Pekka Haavisto, BTF Chairman, announced here Wednesday that a
BTF team would soon begin work with the Interim Civil
Administration component of the United Nations Mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Haavisto, who was in Kosovo and Macedonia last weekend, said
that following an agreement with the U.N. authorities in the
Balkans, the BTF team would design strategies for local
authorities and communities so that they can effectively
participate in the reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
In Pristina last weekend, Haavisto and his team also met with
commanders of K-FOR. K-FOR has started an assessment of the damage
to human settlements and infrastructure in Kosovo, and agreed to
fully cooperate and share their findings with the planned BTF
mission.
</P>
<P>
The BTF mission, Haavisto said, would travel to the Balkans
region this month and concentrate their work at identified
"hot-spots" of environmental risk at locations in Serbia, Kosovo,
Montenegro, Albania, Macedonia and along the Danube River in
Romania/Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
 An earlier U.N. inter-agency mission to the Balkans
recommended that UNEP, together with Habitat and UNDP, carry out a
detailed assessment of the environmental situation with the aim of
identifying specific needs for targeted assistance.
</P>
<P>
This recommendation was echoed by European Union Environment
Ministers at the Council meeting in Luxembourg last month. The
ministers welcomed the efforts of UNEP/Habitat and said it was
necessary to immediately start obtaining reliable and verifiable
information for assessing the type and extent of environmental
consequences of the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana, US Ex-Im Bank sign credit Pact on sea defense wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) - - Ghana's ministry of Finance
Wednesday signed an agreement with the Export-Import Bank (Ex-Im
Bank) of the United States and the Private Export Funding
Corporation for a long-term credit of 93.8 million dollars for the
Keta Sea Defense project.
</P>
<P>
 The loan will be used to purchase U.S.-made equipment to
build a sea. defense wall and other infrastructure to protect the
Keta beach and lagoon in south-east Ghana from erosion, the Ghana
News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
 Ghana's finance Minister Kwame Peprah signed for the
Government while U.S. Ambassador in Ghana Kathryn Dee Robinson
signed for the United States.
</P>
<P>
 The facility comes with a five-year moratorium on interest
payment and will be repayable over a 10-year period starting
September 2004.
</P>
<P>
 The project is expected to bring hope and prevent what could
be catastrophic impact on agriculture, fisheries, commerce and
living conditions of the inhabitants of Keta and surrounding
areas.
</P>
<P>
Miles of land have been lost to the sea which has been lashing
the beaches and causing flooding.
</P>
<P>
 The main components of the construction works to be financed
are Havedzi-Keta main access roads, offshore breakwater at Keta,
groynes and headlands from Kedzi to Keta.
</P>
<P>
 It also provides for beach nourishment, outfall structure at
Kedzi for the lagoon flood control, land reclamation and bird
habitat islands.
</P>
<P>
 Actual construction work is scheduled to take off in
September this year.
</P>
<P>
 The agreement followed Ex-Im Bank's approval of 1.89 million
dollars in 1995 to finance feasibility and engineering study of
the Keta project by Great Lakes Dredge and Dock under the Ex-Im
Bank Engineering Multiplier Program.
</P>
<P>
Ex-Im Bank is an independent U.S. government agency that
assists in financing the export of U.S. goods and services to
industrializing and developing markets all over the world by
providing loans, loan guarantees, and export credit insurance.
</P>
<P>
 Isaac Adjei-Mensah, Minister of Works and Housing, described
the agreement as a major step and an important milestone toward
the implementation of actual constructional works.
</P>
<P>
 He said electricity supply has been extended from
Afiadenyigba to Havedzi, the starting point of the wall, to
facilitate early completion of work.
</P>
<P>
 Adjei-Mensah expressed satisfaction at efforts made to
implement the project, saying, "we have come a long way, and
treaded a very difficult path to reach this stage of the Keta Sea
Defense Project today."
</P>
<P>
 He commended the Presidency for its profound interest and
commitment that has seen to the take-off of the project.
</P>
<P>
 Robinson noted that the project is a major one, the largest
civil works by the bank in West Africa in recent years.
</P>
<P>
 Richard Lowry, Chief Operations Officer and Executive
Vice-President of Great Lakes and Dredge, said they are excited by
the project and are looking forward to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defection Hits Ousted Congolese Rebel Leader's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen of the 26 members of the
Kisangani- based rebel faction led by ousted leader Ernest Wamba
dia Wamba, has defected to the Congolese rebels in Goma, the
Rwanda News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that Wamba's companions have defected to our side,''
 Vice- President of the Rally for Congolese Democracy (RCD) in
Goma, Moise Nyarugabo, was quoted as saying Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said that the defectors, led by Willy Mishiki,
a former member of the RCD assembly before the ouster of Wamba,
had been disappointed because Wamba failed to emerge as a leader
of the rebellion at the peace talks in Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
It is said that Mishiki's group has already signed a letter
distancing themselves from Wamba, said Nyarugabo.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, who is participating in the Lusaka talks aimed at
brokering a cease-fire for the 11-month old conflict, played down
the defection.
</P>
<P>
"We are not aware of the defection. I talked to Mishiki on
Tuesday myself and there was no problem," Wamba was quoted as
saying from Lusaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Urged to Intensify Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- African leaders have been urged to
do more to prevent more people from getting infected with AIDS
which has been hindering the development of Africa for about 20
years.
</P>
<P>
Godfrey Sikipa, UNAIDS consultant, made the appeal at the
ambassadors' meeting here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"HIV/AIDS is not only a problem of health, it is also a
development issue. So much has to be done to prevent rampant
spread of the epidemic and to help those already infected," he
told Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
"The UNAIDS will develop cooperation with OAU to mobilize our
political and community leaders and to mobilize support from the
international community," he added.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS wants African leaders to form multi-sectoral
committees in their respective countries and come up with national
strategic plans which can be supported by many other U.N.
agencies.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the reason for the rampant spread of the
deadly disease, the official blamed it on poverty.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Africa's population is now living under the
poverty line and this is the most important factor causing the
problem, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Africa now has 22 million people infected with HIV/AIDS,
accounting for over two thirds of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS rate has been on the rise in most of sub-Sahara
African countries. It can be as high as 30 percent in some of
those countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
