<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: Sierra Leone Peace Accord Inked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Tejan Kabbah
and rebel leader Foday Sankoh signed a hardly-earned and
long-desired peace accord in Togolese capital Lome on Wednesday
afternoon, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
After signing the accord reached following six weeks' tough
negotiations and a final push-up by a regional mini-summit,
President Kabbah called on his fellow Sierra Leonean people to
learn to "forgive and forget" and to achieve national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The accord, agreed to only on Wednesday morning, stipulates
that the rebels will be disarmed and share power with the elected
Kabbah administration by acquiring several ministerial posts in a
transitional government.
</P>
<P>
But the Nigeria-led west Africa peace-keeping force ECOMOG will
stay in Sierra Leone, according to the document, which was
formerly opposed by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Nigeria, Burkina Faso, Liberia and the host
country Togo were present at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit, called by Togolese President Gnassingbe
Eyadema, current Chairman of the Economic Community of the West
Africa States (ECOWAS), played an important role in removing the
final hurdles on the road to the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
All parties concerned, including Nigeria who has been leading
the ECOMOG in fighting the Sierra Leonean rebels and Liberia and
Burkina Faso who had been allegedly backing the rebels secretly,
were brought together to made a final push for a lasting peace in
the war-torn west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
