<HEADLINE> IDB Assists to Improve Highway and Access Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of a soft loan of 52
million U.S. dollars to Bolivia to upgrade a section of the Pan
American Highway, Bolivia Route No.1. as well as to improve access
roads.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be used to help finance the paving and
upgrading of the 84 kilometers of road connecting Ventilla and
Tarapaya and to improve 23 kilometers of road between Tarapaya and
Potosi, the Washington-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 150 kilometers of access roads will be improved
along the Ventilla-Tarapaya-Potosi stretch.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to stimulate economic growth in the
highland-area served by the roads, improve access of population to
basic services, reduce travel time, enhance the administration of
road transportation and maintenance, and provide temporary
employment opportunities to low-income communities, the IDB said.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is 71.8 million dollars. The IDB
loan is for a 40-year term, with a 10-year grace period, at an
annual interest rate of 1 percent during the grace period and 2
percent thereafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
