<HEADLINE> Cyprus Looks into Fishing Incident With Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Wednesday
said it is looking into an incident during which Turkish troops
are said to have fired shots at Greek Cypriot fishermen.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to establish exactly what happened before we
make any further moves," government sources said, adding that the
government has received reports on the incident, which occurred on
Monday night and early Tuesday morning when the fishermen were out
at sea to cast their fishing nets.
</P>
<P>
However, U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP)
spokeswoman Sarah Russell, said Wednesday that Greek Cypriot
fishermen did cross the security maritime line on two occasions
in the past couple of days.
</P>
<P>
She also said she could not confirm reports that Turkish troops
fired shots and flares on the fishermen at this stage.
</P>
<P>
"We have a report from the Cypriot police and we saw a fishing
boat crossing the maritime security zone by about 450 meters on
Monday and again early Tuesday morning," Russell said.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP has complained to the Cypriot government about what
it called violations of the maritime security zone, on the east of
the Cyprus island, which is effectively an extension of the U.N.-
controlled buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus was established in 1964
and more than 1,200 peacekeepers are patroling the 180-kilometer
dividing line across the country between the rival Greek Cypriots
and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyrus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
