<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Unveils Reassembled Statue of God, Goddess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Museum unveiled on
Wednesday a Pharaonic sculpture of a god and goddess that has been
reconstructed from 250 fragments.
</P>
<P>
The assembly is the fruit of five years of work by Egyptologist
Hourig Sourouzian of the German Institute of Archaeology in Cairo,
who was the first to realize that the pieces of limestone stored
in six different sites in Egypt belonged to a single statue,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture shows Amun - the god of air, creation and empire
- seated with his consort Mut - the goddess of motherhood and
nature. It dates from the reign of King Horemheb (1320-1306 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
As major elements of the gods' bodies are missing, the statue
has been rebuilt on a steel frame of 4.5 meters high with the
fragments held in place by thick pins and epoxy resin.
</P>
<P>
The statue originally stood in Karnak, the Pharaonic city in
Luxor, 520 kilometers south of Cairo. Mut's head, the first piece
to be excavated, was found in 1870. Other fragments were
subsequently dug up and stored or put on display in Cairo and
Karnak.
</P>
<P>
Sourouzian encountered the fragments while looking for pieces
of other group statues for her doctoral thesis. The breakthrough
came in 1994 when she discovered Amun's head in a storeroom in the
Egyptian Museum. During the next three years, she recognized more
fragments that belonged to the statue.
</P>
<P>
The work of fitting the fragments together began in September
1998.
</P>
<P>
Excavation continues in Karnak, and just last month workmen
found a sliver of Mut's cheek. It was glued on, and the statue,
consisting of 78 fragments, was finished Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-07 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses Italy of Supporting PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey Wednesday harshly criticized
Italy for adopting encouraging approach towards members and
sympathizers of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), said
Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli here.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli called on the Italian government to act with prudence
in order to preserve the "solid foundations" on which the essence
of Turkish-Italian relations are based.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that PKK supporters are increasingly given a free
hand to carry out violent activities in Italy is a grave
development," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the Italian authorities to act realistically and
with prudence...in order to prevent further shadows from being
cast on the friendly relations between our two countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, which are against the death penalty, called
on Turkey not to hang PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan after he was
sentenced to death on June 29 on charges of treason and separatism.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, two groups of PKK supporters briefly occupied a
Turkish commercial office and one room of the Italian Foreign
Trade Ministry in Rome.
</P>
<P>
The attackers walked out freely and no action was taken
against them by the Italian police.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Italy have been at odds since last November when
Ocalan arrived in Rome and was hosted there at a luxurious villa
for several months.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral tensions have mounted again recently following the
death sentence on Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli pointed out that "although the present developments
could be seen as the result of Italy's own dynamics, we cannot
tolerate statements and acts which constitute an interference into
Turkey's democratic system and judicial procedures."
</P>
<P>
Following harsh remarks by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit on Tuesday, Turkish Ambassador in Rome Necati Utkan was
summoned to the Italian Foreign Ministry on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984. Conflicts between
the Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have claimed
over 37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and has ever since been detained on Imrali Island
in Marmara Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
