<HEADLINE> More Women Have Access to Family Planning Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Population Office
of Ethiopia said Wednesday that 10 percent of the Ethiopian women
are having access to family planning services compared to only
four percent some six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here to mark the World Population Day
which falls on July 11, Negussie Tefera, head of the National
Population Office of Ethiopia, said encouraging achievements have
been made in the implementation of the national population policy
both at the federal and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
Negussie said that women, health, social and environmental
protection policies have contributed to the implementation of the
national population policy.
</P>
<P>
The national population policy, which was launched six years
ago, states that the number of children in a family should not
exceed four, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, with a population of 60 million, is the third largest
 population country in Africa only following Nigeria and Egypt.
