<HEADLINE> U.N. Sends Team to Baghdad to Close UNSCOM Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A team of independent
experts is scheduled to leave for Baghdad on Thursday to close a
U.N. laboratory reportedly containing dangerous chemicals, a U.N.
spokesman said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The team comprises four chemical experts from the Organization
for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) in the Hague and an
independent biological weapons expert, spokesman Manorl de Almeida
e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
According to a list released by the U.N. spokesman's office,
the experts are led by Dirk van Niekerk, a South African chemical
production technologist.
</P>
<P>
Team members are Ms. Li Hua, analytical chemist from China,
Sergey Orlov, analytical chemicist from Russia and Miroslav
Miklasz, medical doctor from Poland.
</P>
<P>
The one not belonging to OPCW is Wolfgang Beyer, microbiologist
at Hohenheim University in Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The team is expected to arrive in Baghdad next week, with stops
in Bahrain and Jordan over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
It is going to be accompanied by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's special representative Prakash Shah and four senior
foreign diplomats, Almeida e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
The chemical substances, said to include 1 kilogram of mustard
gas and V-X agents were left behind by inspectors of the U.N.
Special Commission on Iraq (UNSCOM) who were evacuated on December
16 ahead of U.S.-British air-strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Since then Baghdad has not resumed cooperation with UNSCOM, but
agreed to accept independent experts to close the lab and remove
the gases seen dangerous in case of a power failure or high
temperature.  
</P>
</TEXT>
