<HEADLINE> African Leaders Urged to Liberate Child Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior official with the
Pan-African Youth Movement has appealed to African leaders to do
more to save the child soldiers on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mushokolwa Leonidas, deputy secretary-general of the
specialized agency of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in
the field of youth, said here Wednesday evening that the problem
of child soldiers demands attention from all African leaders.
</P>
<P>
Leonidas said that his organization is currently carrying out a
program aimed at sensitizing the leaders on the problem with a
view to bringing the issue to an end.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 100,000 child soldiers have been
employed in armed conflicts on the continent. The war experience
will damage these children both psychologically and physically,
the official warned.
</P>
<P>
The youth organization would send officials to two refugee
camps to assess the nature of the problem of child soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The child soldiers should have the normal environment in which
other children enjoy, he noted. Once the child soldiers are
liberated, they would return home and receive normal education.
</P>
<P>
The Pan-African Youth Movement was set up on April 26, 1962.
Its prime aim is to address and solve youth problems such as
unemployment, education and others. 
</P>
