<HEADLINE> S. African Presence in Congo (K) Subject to Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's possible
peace-keeping role in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) would
be subject to a long approval process, Defense Ministry spokesman
Puso Tladi said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to reports that the South African National Defense
Force (SANDF) could send troops within 24 hours of a cease-fire
agreement, Tladi said any involvement depended entirely on
receiving a request for assistance from either the United Nations,
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) or the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the type of involvement would have to be
determined, then approved in accordance with the budgets of the
requesting organization and the relevant South African ministry.
</P>
<P>
Any deployment would need cabinet approval and parliamentary
ratification.
</P>
<P>
"It has been agreed that there will be a Joint Monitoring
Commission and we have definitely agreed to participate in that,"
Tladi said. "The monitoring of the cease-fire doesn't necessarily
mean the sending of soldiers."
</P>
<P>
He said news reports Wednesday gave the impression, after an
interview with Defense Minister Patrick Lekota, that Lekota had
said South African troops could be deployed in the DRC in less
than 24 hours after a cease- fire was formally signed, ready to
face any eventuality.
</P>
<P>
"This is not so. What he said was that the monitoring of the
cease-fire could commence within 24 hours after an agreement has
been signed by all participants and role players.
</P>
<P>
"This is in terms of an understanding agreed to in principle
during discussion in Lusaka, which does not make reference to
SANDF unit deployment, and the many processes and drills that
precede such a deployment."
</P>
<P>
Tladi said last year's Lesotho operation was different to the
situation in the DRC. "It was a coup and a big disruption that
came suddenly (in Lesotho). The DRC is a long drawn-out problem."
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswana troops entered Lesotho last
September under the auspices of the SADC to restore order in the
mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, a draft cease-fire document for the DRC
was finally adopted Wednesday by foreign and defense ministers of
the countries involved in the conflict and rebel representatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
