after his talks with Mozambican Planning and Finance Minister
Tomaz Salomao in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese minister did not disclose any details about the
debt rescheduling, but pledged that his government is willing to
contribute to Mozambique's debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Portugal will do more in multi-lateral negotiations within the
Paris Club for more debt write-off, he added.
</P>
<P>
Franco noted that the Mozambican government has made great
efforts to achieve economic growth, keep marco-economic balance
and strengthen democracy.
</P>
<P>
The international financial institutions including the World
Bank have written off some 3.7 billion dollars of Mozambique's
debts.
</P>
<P>
Salomao said that during their three-day meeting, the two
governments also reached agreement in such fields as human
resources development, customs and insurance.
</P>
<P>
But the Mozambican minister denied that some Portuguese
departments will take the place of the British Crown Agents in
managing the Mozambican customs.
</P>
<P>
Franco, who arrived in Maputo Sunday for a three-day visit to
the southern African country, also held meeting with Mozambican
President Joaquim Chissano. He will leave Maputo for home later
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
