<HEADLINE> OAU to Be More Efficient, Transparent: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU), which has been under fire for low efficiency, is trying to
trim itself into a "more efficient body to meet the new
millennium", an OAU official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Dagash, spokesman of the biggest organization in
Africa, said at a press conference here during the two-day OAU
ambassadors' meeting that the OAU will be transformed into a
"human, fair and transparent organization" after the restructuring
program.
</P>
<P>
The 18-month-long streamlining program, which will cut the
organization of about 600 member by 200, is expected to complete
by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
A thinner OAU administration, he said, will help the
organization meet the challenges in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
OAU is to hold the 35th annual summit in Algiers, Algeria, from
July 12 to 14, at a time when the continent is facing "daunting
challenges in the socio-economic and political fields, and in
context of a rapidly changing world."
</P>
<P>
The African people are facing severe hardships like poverty,
illiteracy, diseases, unemployment, rising crimes, and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming summit, the last before the advent of the next
millennium, is widely regarded as a chance for the African leaders
to get better prepared for new challenges ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
