<HEADLINE> UK Post Offices Issue Passport Extensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- All main post offices in the UK
began issuing free passport extensions on Wednesday in a bid to
ease the current backlog crisis, which has resulted in thousands
of people cancelling their holidays or business trips.
</P>
<P>
Extensions of up to two years are being given for full
passports that are either about to expire or have expired in the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
Those caught in the current backlog of applications can go to
any of 1,500 main post offices across the country. Applicants will
only need proof of identity such as their old passport or a
driving licence.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, there are some 530,000 outstanding applications,
even though new queuing arrangements and a national phone centre
have been set up.
</P>
<P>
The delays have been reportedly caused by a combination of new
computer technology introduced last October at the same time as
new rules requiring children and babies to have their own
passports.
</P>
<P>
British Home Secretary Jack Straw has admitted that the service
will not be back to normal before September. Even that deadline
would depend on a predicted big drop in passport applications
happening "at some stage next month".
</P>
<P>
An extra 100 staff are being recruited to help tackle the
backlog, in addition to 300 workers already hired, and staff are
still working into the night and at weekends to try to cut delays,
according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
Straw insisted there was "no suggestion whatsoever" that the
crisis was the fault of the passport staff, who were working
"round the clock". But queues of anxious holiday-makers have
embarrassed ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
