<HEADLINE> Russian Duma, NATO Parliament to Resume Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma and the NATO
Parliamentary Assembly plan to resume cooperation shortly, the
Interfax news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Duma chairman Gennady Seleznyov
and Javier Ruperes, head of the NATO Parliamentary Assembly,
following their talks in St. Petersburg, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The activities of the Coordinating Interparliamentary Committee
were suspended when NATO started its 78-day air strikes on
Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
An understanding has been reached that representatives of the
Russian lower house of parliament will meet with Ruperes in
October "to discuss further cooperation," Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
"Even when the situation is most dramatic for their countries,
parliamentarians must meet and look for solutions," Seleznyov
said.
</P>
<P>
Ruperes, for his part, welcomed the start of improvement in
relations between the NATO and Russian parliaments.
</P>
<P>
While the two sides analyze the developments in Kosovo in
different lights, they think alike about the joint rebuilding of
the region, Ruperes said. 
</P>
