<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Blasts Britain Over Gold Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Wednesday accused
Britain of breaking a promise not to go ahead with gold sales
without prior consultation and retracted its initial conditional
support for the intended gold sales by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"The South African government finds both incomprehensible and
unacceptable the insensitivity of the British government and its
monetary authorities to the pleas of gold-producing countries,"
government spokesman Joel Netshitenzhe told a news briefing in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"This behavior, and the decisions of other industrialized
countries and the IMF on the public handling of gold sales, is
having the effect of defeating the very objectives that they
profess to pursue," the spokesman read from a cabinet statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the South African government would continue
discussions with the countries and organizations concerned to
ensure that their aim of relieving the debt burden of developing
countries did not "degenerate into a beggaring of the economies of
the intended beneficiaries. "
</P>
<P>
South African Minerals and Energy Minister Phumzile
Mlambo-Ngcuka said that his country had formally reversed its
position regarding the sale of gold by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Asked why, she said: "The amount being sold is what makes the
difference. Taking into consideration all the events and the
situation now, we realized that we need to revisit that position."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's British auction of 25 tons of gold saw the metal's
price sliding to a fresh 20-year low of 256.10 U.S. dollars per
ounce.
</P>
<P>
Ngcuka said President Thabo Mbeki has been in discussions with
some of the "major countries" and their central banks,
particularly Britain, Germany, France, Japan, and the United
States, regarding their intention to sell some of their bullion.
</P>
<P>
"In relation to the UK, there was an agreement that... before
they went out to embark on any sales they would revert back to us,
which in this case did not happen. What has now happened is quite
unacceptable and of concern to us."
</P>
<P>
The other countries undertook not to go ahead with such sales.
</P>
<P>
The minister said South Africa intended sending a
representative to Britain to ask for help from "some of our
partners" to ensure that the current trend in that country did not
continue.
</P>
<P>
The South African government would also maintain pressure on
the other countries not to follow Britain's suit.
</P>
<P>
It would furthermore seek a common position on this matter with
other indebted gold-producing countries," Ngcuka said.
</P>
<P>
This would be done by consultations with the embassies of such
countries, and visits by Ngcuka's deputy to some key gold
producers such as Mali, Ghana and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
South African Finance Minister Trevor Manuel was on his way to
a meeting with his counterparts in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), where this issue would also be on
the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Ngcuka called on employers not to react to the current gold
crisis by retrenching workers.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is the biggest gold producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
"There is evidence that there is more demand than supply,"
Ngcuka said. "Gold is likely to recover and we don't think we are
seeing the end of this industry."
</P>
<P>
On the pending liquidation of East Rand Proprietary Mines,
Ngcuka said, this could not be solely blamed on the current
situation in the gold market.
</P>
<P>
The mine, she said, had been in trouble for the past 10 years,
and its management should have foreseen the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
She said the mine has not reached the end of its life, and in
order to give it another chance the government would assist in
efforts to find a new investor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
