<HEADLINE> U.S. Firefighters to Contain Largest Western Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The largest fire burning in the
West of the United States, a 25,000-hectare blaze feeding on
pinyon pine, juniper and cheat grass in central Utah State, is
expected to be declared controlled by late Wednesday, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The fire twice drove residents of the Eureka and Mammoth areas
in Utah from their homes over the weekend, but no one was injured
and only three abandoned shacks burned.
</P>
<P>
Over 420 firefighters have been working on the fire and they
were expected to be released beginning Wednesday, the reports
quoted fire information officer Jerry Rohnert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, a 3,600-hectare fire near Genola, 95 kilometers
south of Salt Lake City, was 90 percent contained and control was
projected for late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Near Hesperia, California State, a blaze in the San Bernardino
National Forest forced about 70 people to evacuate their homes but
they were allowed to return late Tuesday. The fire was 80 percent
contained Wednesday after burning through 1,100 hectares of brush,
said Bill Peters of the California Department of Forestry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
