<HEADLINE> Situation in C. Angola Returns to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The situation around the central
highland city of Huambo has returned to normal thanks to a series
of operations by the Angolan government, Governor of Huambo
Province Paulo Kassoma said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The governor noted that the armed forces, national police and
militia should keep alert on possible fresh attacks by the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between the government army and the UNITA troops
had picked up since mid-June.
</P>
<P>
Kassoma spoke highly of the government's re-taking of the
strategic Mount Mbazi, some 40 kms north of Huambo city last
Thursday. The UNITA troops had launched attacks against the
provincial capital from the mount, threatening Huambo's airport,
the only life line of the city.
</P>
<P>
On June 19, some 1,000 UNITA troops launched sudden attacks
against the town of Caala, some 23 kms west of Huambo, resuming
long-range artillery bombardment of the city. The escalating
tension has created a new wave of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Food supply is far from enough in the area. It was reported
that malnutrition was spreading there like anything. Everyday the
nutrition center in Caala has to receive more than 200 patients
while it is capable of taking only 150. 
</P>
