<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Cancels Poland Trip for N.Ireland Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has canceled a visit to Poland in order to concentrate on the
continuing crisis in the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
The move came as the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) warned that it
probably could not accept the latest peace proposals without
further assurances from the government. The party's ruling
executive is due to meet Friday when it could make a decision on
whether or not to sign up to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have also been raised by the Orange Order's decision
to move its traditional 12 July rally in Belfast to the south of
the city in protest against the banning of the local lodge's
parade through a mainly nationalist area.
</P>
<P>
Blair was to have flown to Warsaw Sunday and to have returned
home Monday or Tuesday. But his spokesman said the prime minister
had regretfully decided that he could not go.
</P>
<P>
UUP leader and Northern Ireland First Minister David Trimble
warned that the government was making it increasingly more
difficult for his party to make up its mind.
</P>
<P>
The unionist leader said uncertainty was deepening and every
time he sought clarification of the latest UK-Irish proposals he
was left with more questions than answers, according to a BBC
report.
</P>
<P>
Under the plans advanced last week, the unionists accepted Sinn
Fein into a governmental executive next week and a weapons
decommissioning process would start within days.
</P>
<P>
If the Irish Republican Army did not begin disarm its weapons
soon after, then Sinn Fein would face exclusion from the executive
under legislation to be rushed through the British and Irish
parliaments, Blair told the Parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Trimble, his party's great worry was that "we make
the sacrifice in terms of being prepared to enter into the
administration with unreconstructed terrorists, but then they
refuse to decommission, but the automatic failsafe isn't automatic
and that we come under pressure by people saying it's Sinn Fein
and they are not the same as the IRA and they are trying and let's
not throw this all out."
</P>
<P>
Trimble said he did not think the party could make a decision
on the peace plan until it had more details from government.
However, he made it clear he would not give up on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein appears to be largely supportive of the peace deal,
but it has demanded assurances that the government would not halt
the early release of paramilitary prisoners if the IRA failed to
disarm.
</P>
<P>
Downing Street insists that it has the power to take such
action under the Northern Ireland Sentences Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
