<HEADLINE> Ghana to Spend $60M on Village Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Ghana will spend a total of 60
million U.S. dollars on its five-year Village Infrastructure
Project to enhance the quality of life of the villagers in the
rural areas, the Ghana News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Salifu Mahama, Zone One Coordinator of the project said that it
is aimed at increasing the transfer of financial and technical
resources to the rural people to serve as a catalyst for
development and sustaining basic village level infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The zone one comprises of the Northern, Upper East and Upper
West regions.
</P>
<P>
Mahama said the project is being financed by the International
Development Agency, the International Fund for Agriculture
Development, the Ghanaian government, district assemblies and
other related agencies.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator said the project also seeks to construct and
rehabilitate about 92 dugouts and other small surface water
sources in the selected districts throughout the country to
provide good drinking water for the rural people and their
animals.
</P>
<P>
He also said about 270 kilometers of village tracks and trails
would be developed at the beneficiary communities. 
</P>
