<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Peace Pact in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan On Wednesday warmly welcomed the signing of a peace
agreement between the government and the Revolutionary United
Front (RUF) in Sierra Leone, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He "calls on the parties to the peace accord to honor their
commitments and he offers the vigilant support of the United
Nations in their efforts at reconciliation and rebuilding," a
statement issued by U.N. spokesman's office in New York said.
</P>
<P>
Annan "salutes the political courage of President Kabbah, who
persisted in the search for a political solution, and of the
political leaders of the region who supported that effort," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Annan especially mentioned President Eyadema of Togo, the
current Chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
who hosted the latest talks, President Obasanjo of Nigeria,
President Taylor of Liberia and President Campoare of Burkina
Faso, the current Chairman of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and RUF leader Foday
Sanko signed the peace accord in the capital of Lome on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal ends eight years of civil war killing thousands and
leaving over half of the West African country's 4.7 million people
displaced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
