<HEADLINE> Europe's Main Stock Markets Close In Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Europe's main markets all closed
firmly in the red Wednesday as a weak start on Wall Street and
profit-taking continued to hit the markets.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index ended the session down 0.35 percent at
6,597.4, a fall of 23.2 points from Tuesday's record close.
</P>
<P>
UK investors were cautious as the two-day Bank of England's
Monetary Policy Committee meeting on interest rate got underway.
</P>
<P>
Surprisingly strong UK economic data released Tuesday reduced
the chances of a further rate cut, but the continued weakness in
sterling against the dollar could influence the committee's
thinking.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the electronically-traded Xetra Dax in
Frankfurt ended down 0.43 percent, or 24.4 points, at 5,588.50.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said profit-taking continued with computer software
company SAP and Mannesmann making heavy losses after Wall Street's
negative opening put further pressure on closing market prices.
</P>
<P>
BMW was up 18.00 euros at 707.00. But shares in DaimlerChrysler
and VW fell after a report in the Financial Times newspaper
suggested that VW will cut output by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Paris shares closed lower on continued profit-taking from
recent highs. The Cac 40 index closed 30.31 points lower at
4,662.20. 
</P>
