<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Cognitive Decline Not Normal in Aging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cognitive decline is not a
normal part of aging for the majority of elderly people, according
to a study conducted by researchers at University of California.
</P>
<P>
In fact, only people with high levels of atherosclerosis or
diabetes and also those with the apolipoprotein E4 (Apo4E) gene
associated with Alzheimer's disease are both at risk for a decline
in cognitive ability as they age.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted at the UC Davis School of Medicine,
tracked changes in cardiovascular health and cognitive function in
almost 6,000 senior citizens annually over a 10-year period. The
results of the study were reported in the July 7 issue of the
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of individuals evaluated in the study showed no
significant decline in cognitive function over the study period,
the medical school said in a release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the researchers found that the greatest loss of
cognitive ability occurred in people who had both high levels of
atherosclerosis or diabetes and an Apo4E gene. These individuals
were eight times more likely to show a decline in function
compared to people with a low level of atherosclerosis and no
genetic predisposition. Individuals with an E4 allele were
three-to-four times more likely to show a decline in function than
those without this genotype. And those with high levels of
atherosclerosis were three times more likely to show a loss of
function than those without atherosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
Cognitive function is defined as the intellectual process by
which one becomes aware of, perceives, or comprehends ideas. It
involves all aspects of perception, thinking, reasoning and
remembering.
</P>
<P>
The school said that other studies of the elderly have shown
that people with the ApoE4 gene have a higher risk of Alzheimer's
disease. But it was not clear what role atherosclerosis or
diabetes might play. Now the current study shows that the risk of
cognitive impairment or even dementia in those who have a genetic
predisposition may be reduced by preventing atherosclerosis. And
doctors know a lot about preventing cardiovascular disease and not
much about preventing cognitive impairment or dementia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tobacco Industry Found Liable in Class-action Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A Florida jury found Wednesday
U.S. cigarette makers produced a defective product that causes
emphysema, lung cancer and other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The six-person jury in the first class-action lawsuit by
smokers ever to go to trial ruled that America's biggest tobacco
companies must pay unspecified damages for conspiring to hide the
dangers of smoking.
</P>
<P>
Their decision could prove to be the industry's most dire
courtroom loss yet, since the plaintiffs are seeking at least 200
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit was filed in 1994 on behalf of as many as 500,000
sick or dead Florida smokers and their survivors. The plaintiffs'
attorney had said potential damages -- to be assessed in a later
series of trials -- could range from 200 billion dollars to 500
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The defendants were the nation's five biggest cigarette makers
and two industry groups: Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., Lorillard Tobacco Co.,
Liggett Group Inc., the Council for Tobacco Research and the
Tobacco Institute.
</P>
<P>
The smokers claimed the industry deceived them about the dangers
of smoking, hid research results, stopped scientific work that
promised to produce safer cigarettes and advertised to children.
</P>
<P>
Attorney Stanley Rosenblatt called it a "rampant and cynical
long-standing pattern of fraud."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
