<HEADLINE> Asia to Have Chance for Fifth World Cup Qualifying S pot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- As part of a deal approved by
soccer's world governing body FIFA, Asia will have a chance to put a
fifth team in the 2002 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
During the women's World Cup tournament, FIFA's executive
committee had a meeting here on Tuesday and approved the deal.
</P>
<P>
Asia was originally set to get four spots in the 2002 World Cup:
two for co-hosts South Korea and Japan, and two for its regional
qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
The third-place team in the Asian qualifying tournament will
play the 14th team in European qualifying, FIFA president Sepp
Blatter said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Europea has the most spots in the field, with 14 qualifiers and
defending champions France.
</P>
<P>
Asia, which had threatened a boycott, had four teams at the 1998
World Cup. Iran, which finished fourth in Asian qualifying
tournament, won a playoff with Oceania champions Australia.
</P>
<P>
The deal must be approved by the Asian and European governing
bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
