<HEADLINE> Italian Police Finds Bomb in Turkish Mosque </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Italian Police announced Wednesday
that a one kilo bomb, complete with three detonators has been
found in one of the two Turkish mosques on the outskirts of
Italian north city of Como Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said that an anonymous caller phoned the
religious center Tuesday night and warned that the place was about
to be blown up.
</P>
<P>
The caller, who spoke in Turkish, said that he belonged to a
"Turkish anti-fascist movement".
</P>
<P>
Police evacuated homes near the mosque and closed the area to
traffic while they defused the explosive device, safely completing
the operation shortly after Tuesday midnight.
</P>
<P>
There was no timer attached to the bomb, which had been hidden
in a heater situated in an outside courtyard, and it was unclear
if it could really have gone off.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish community is the largest foreign group living in
Como, and is held to be on good terms with local Kurds.
</P>
<P>
But the city has recently seen a spate of anti-Turkish protests
and wall scribbling attributed to hard left-wing Turkish groups.
</P>
<P>
Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan were suspected of being
behind the latest incident.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was recently sentenced to death for treason by Turkish
prosecutors, who held him responsible for a 14-year campaign for
Kurdish self-rule in which more than 29,000 people have died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
