<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. CEO Confidence Increases in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Chief executives' confidence
in the nation's economy increased by 10 points in the second
quarter, the Conference Board, a U.S. prominent research group,
said Wednesday in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Measure of Business Confidence in the
second quarter jumped to 56 from the previous quarter's reading of
46. A reading of more than 50 points reflects more positive than
negative responses.
</P>
<P>
"The continued strength of the U.S. economy is no doubt partly
responsible for the strong current assessment of economic
conditions on the part of chief executives," said Lynn Franco,
associate director of the Conference Board's Consumer Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
The report said, CEO's assessment of current economic
conditions improved substantially from the first quarter survey.
About 41 percent of the CEO's feel economic conditions have gotten
better over the past six months, up from 25 percent and those who
feel conditions have deteriorated over the past six months
declined to 7 percent from about 19 percent in the first quarter,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders' confidence regarding conditions in their own
industries was significantly more upbeat, the report said, adding
that close to 53 percent of CEOs fell conditions are better than
six months ago, up from about 24 percent last quarter.
</P>
<P>
The report said regarding profit expectations during the next
12 months, more than three out of every four executives anticipate
increases, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said among chief executive officers expecting
profits to increase, 46 percent cite cost reductions as the main
source of improvement and 41 percent cite new technology as the
most likely source. Only 9 percent foresee an increase in
market/demand growth as the main source of improvement, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Exchange Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China today
issued the market exchange rates in RMB yuan against three major
currencies. The middle price of RMB yuan against convertible
currencies is mainly based on the closing price of the preceding
interbank trading.
</P>
<P>
 The designated foreign exchange trading banks will decide the
exchange rates in RMB yuan against other convertible currencies
according to the tone of the international exchange market and the
rules of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
 Market Exchange Rates (in RMB yuan)
</P>
