<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lamb Tariff by U.S. Unacceptable: New Zealand PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley said here Thursday that the United States decision to
impose lamb import tariffs is "totally unacceptable and will lead
to World Trade Organization action."
</P>
<P>
"New Zealanders are angry and deeply disappointed at a decision
that will, in effect, be a tax on our lamb exporters. The U.S.
decision will for the next three years limit our exports and
prevent our non-subsidized industry from further developing the
U.S. lamb market," the prime minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand cannot and will not let the matter rest," Shipley
said.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand prime minister made the remarks in response to
U.S. President Bill Clinton's Thursday endorsement of an
across-the-board tariff on all imports of lamb from New Zealand
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.S. trade restrictions, the U.S. will impose
in-quota tariff of nine percent on imports up to 31,851,151
kilograms, equivalent to the 1998 level of exports from New
Zealand and Australia, in the first year of the remedy. The
in-quota tariff will be reduced to six percent in the second year
and three percent in the third year. At the same time, the U.S.
will impose out-of-quota tariff of 40 percent in the first year,
reducing to 32 percent in the second year and 24 percent in the
third year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CASS, Japanese Embassy Join Hands in Poverty Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences (CASS) and the Japanese embassy here announced Wednesday
that they'll join hands in helping a northern Chinese county get
rid of poverty.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that CASS will study and put forward
a feasible poverty-fighting plan for Danfeng County, a mountainous
county in the northwest China province of Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese embassy will help promote governmental and non-
governmental economic cooperation with the county, one of the
poorest in China.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the embassy said that Japanese entrepreneurs and
individuals here will be called upon to participate in the poverty-
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Danfeng county and the embassy also signed an agreement here
Wednesday. The latter pledged to donate about 80,000 U.S. dollars
to help build two primary schools, three clinics and some water
supply facilities in the county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
