<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development of New Zealand's Wind Resource Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- "You have the best wind resource
in the world but you are refusing to develop it," an international
wind power expert was quoted Thursday by the Dominion as saying at
a Wellington seminar on wind power this week.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wellington-based newspaper, Dr. Andrew Garrad,
who is recognized as one of the world's leading wind energy
experts and is now working for British-based company Garrad
Hassan, the biggest wind energy consultancy in Europe, told the
seminar, "Your resource is phenomenal in global terms. You could
easily run the whole electricity system off the wind."
</P>
<P>
In theory, Garrad said, New Zealand has enough wind to provide
the country's all electricity needs.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago, there was a wind farm proposed for Baring
Head at the entrance to Wellington harbor but the project was
dropped because the local people were concerned a wind farm would
be as noisy as a helicopter and would sabotage the beautiful
natural scenery.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Garrad suggested wind farms be built around New Zealand in
places where the existing power system is weak.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand power companies can also combine hydro power
stations with wind farms in a way that almost no one else in the
world can," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Use hydro as storage and the wind when it is available," he
said. "That would significantly enhance the value of the wind."
</P>
<P>
At present New Zealand has an annual generation capacity of
about 8,000 megawatts and 75 percent of its total electricity is
produced by hydro generation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Denounces U.S. Decision on Lamb Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister for
International Trade Lockwood Smith here Thursday denounced the
United States decision to impose restrictions on imports of New
Zealand lamb.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the New Zealand minister said: "It's bitterly
disappointing that the U.S. has chosen this approach."
</P>
<P>
"In applying these trade restrictions," he said, "the U.S. has
turned its back on a very constructive proposal from Meat New
Zealand and its Australian counterpart, and allowed its long
standing reputation as a supporter of free and open trade to be
sullied by giving in to short-sighted protectionist sentiment."
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's trade with the U.S. is fair, Smith said, adding
the U.S. unwise decision sends unfortunate signals, particularly
in the year when the U.S. will host the World Trade Organization
(WTO) ministerial meeting which is expected to launch the next
round of trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand will not take today's (U.S.) decision lying
down... We will respond according to New Zealand's best
interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday
announced that he has approved an across-the-board tariff on all
imports of lamb from New Zealand and Australia in response to the
U.S. sheep meat industry's application for "safeguard action".
</P>
<P>
According to New Zealand Minister Smith, the U.S. decision will
 impose costs of approximately 24 million NZ dollars (13 million
U.S. dollars) on New Zealand's lamb industry over the next three
years. It will also limit New Zealand's legitimate trade
expectations by choking off future prospects of growth with the
heavy out-of-quota tariff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
