<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Opens Gold Account in Universiade Swimming Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Australia eventually opened
its gold account by taking two out of the six at stake from the
pool as the swimming competitions entered the fourth day at the
20th World University Games Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
After Adam Pine clocked the fastest time of 53.81 seconds to
take his first-ever gold medal in the men's 100-meter butterfly,
the Australian quartet triumphed again when pace-leader Russia was
disqualified in the 4x100 meters freestyle relay in the open-air
Son Hugo pool.
</P>
<P>
The Australians timed 3:23.05, beating Italy to second in 3:23.
60 and the United States third in 3:24.16.
</P>
<P>
However, the Americans still added two more to its swimming
gold tally to 11, nearly half of the 24 titles taken away as the
swimming competitions concluded its fourth-day events.
</P>
<P>
Mark Warkentin touched home first in the men's 400-meter
freestyle event by a considerable margin, clocking in 3:53.41,
while compatriots Amy Balcebzak and Amanda Beard finished one-two
in the women's 100-meter breaststroke in 1:09.54 and 1:10.23
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The other two swimming golds of the day were split by Spaniard
Maria Pelaez and Romanian I. Diaconescu.
</P>
<P>
Pelaez awarded the hosts its first gold medal at the
Universiade when she edged over Chinese Pang Ran to claim the 200-
meter butterfly in 2:12.34.
</P>
<P>
China is still seeking its first swimming gold medal as only
second-string athletes were dispatched for the games.
</P>
<P>
However, Pang, the former national champion, already improved
her personal best by nearly three seconds for China's first
swimming medal in the Games, a silver, in 2:12.51.
</P>
<P>
Romania also choked up its first swimming gold medal through
Diaconescu who clocked the best in the first event of the day in
56.65 seconds for the women's 100-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Of the 24 swimming gold medals in the first four days, the
United States nearly halved the tally by taking the lion's share
of 11, followed by Japan and Russia, who failed to add a single
one on Wednesday after its victory in the 4x100 meters freestyle
was disqualified, with three each.
</P>
<P>
Both Australia and the Czech Republic bagged two apiece, while
South Africa, Spain and Romania also joined the rank of champions
with one apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
