<P>
LUANDA -- The situation around the central highland city of
Huambo has returned to normal thanks to a series of operations by
the Angolan government, Governor of Huambo Province Paulo Kassoma
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The governor noted that the armed forces, national police and
militia should keep alert on possible fresh attacks by the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA). (Angola-
Military Situation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- The ministers of foreign affairs and defense
finalized the draft cease-fire agreement on the conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) on Wednesday evening here in
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Presidential Affairs Minister Eric Silwamba said at a
press conference that the regional ministers met in Lusaka from
June 29 to July 7, 1999 to finalize the draft cease-fire agreement
on the conflict in the DRC and the Modalities and Time-table for
the implementation of the cease-fire. (Zambia-Congo (K) Peace
Pact)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's most popular moderate daily Salam (Hello) was
closed down on Wednesday by Iranian conservative-dominated
judiciary, the Islamic Republic News Agency(IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that the closure decree was announced by
the judiciary through telephone call to the daily, which has
strongly supported President Mohammad Khatami since his election
in 1997. (Iran-Daily-Closed)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee said Wednesday that India would watch for the results of
Pakistan's intention to withdraw from the Indian side of the Line
of Control (LOC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference of chief ministers here, Vajpayee said,
"We are informed that Pakistan has agreed to withdraw. We will
watch for results on the grounds. In the meantime our operations
shall continue unabated." (India-Pakistan-Troops Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KATHMANDU -- A cargo plane of the German Lufthansa Airlines
