<HEADLINE> Fiat, Mitsubishi Reach Accord on New Sports Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Italian automaker Fiat and the
Japanese vehicle company Mitsubishi Wednesday struck a deal for
jointly producing a new four-wheel-drive sports utility car in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Fiat, which will invest 250 billion lire (about 135 million U.S.
dollars) in the project, will be responsible for the car's design
and styling, while Mitsubishi, with its expertise in four-wheel-
drive vehicles, will produce the chassis and engine.
</P>
<P>
Production is scheduled to begin in 2001 at the Pininfarina
plant near Turin. The two groups plan to build 30,000 cars each
year, taking roughly 10 percent of the European market in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
The car will allow Fiat to complete its range of vehicles and
at the same time renew Mitsubishi's range of four-wheel-drive
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The initial accord for the sports utility car is expected to
lead to further collaboration between the Italian and Japanese
groups.
</P>
<P>
"Fiat Auto and Mitsubishi Motors have agreed to continue
negotiations in coming weeks for further collaboration on a
technical level," a Fiat statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
