<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Keeps Slim Lead in Gold Tally at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Despite its drought of gold
medals of the day, Russia still paces over the United States by
one in the gold tally while Spain tasted its first-ever gold medal
as the 20th World University Games were half way through on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The quartet of Russian men swimmers were disqualified from the
4x100 meters freestyle relay, enabling another swimming power
Australia to eventually open its gold account with two in the
fourth-day swimming competitions.
</P>
<P>
Romania also choked up its first swimming gold medal through I.
Diaconescu who clocked the best in the first event of the day in
56.65 seconds from the women's 100-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
However, the Americans still added two more to its swimming
gold tally to 11, nearly halving the 24 titles given away so far
at the Universiade.
</P>
<P>
Mark Warkentin touched home first in the men's 400-meter
freestyle in 3:53.41, while Amy Balcebzak and Amanda Beard
finished one-two in the women's 100-meter breaststroke in 1:09.54
and 1:10.23 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Adam Pine clocked the fastest time of 53.81 seconds to award
Australia its first-ever gold medal in the men's 100-meter
butterfly at the open-air Son Hugo pool.
</P>
<P>
The Australians timed 3:23.05, beating Italy to second in 3:23.
60 and the United States the third place in 3:24.16.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Maria Pelaez awarded the host its first gold medal
when she edged over Chinese Pang Ran to claim the 200-meter
butterfly in 2:12.34.
</P>
<P>
China is still seeking its first swimming gold medal as only
second-string athletes were dispatched for the games.
</P>
<P>
However, Pang, the former national champion, already improved
her personal best by nearly three seconds for China's first-ever
swimming silver medal in 2:12.51.
</P>
<P>
Of the 24 swimming gold medals in the first four days, the
United States took the lion's share of 11, followed by Japan and
Russia, with three each.
</P>
<P>
Both Australia and the Czech Republic bagged home two apiece,
while South Africa, Spain and Romania also joined the rank of
champions with one each.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday also produced other two titles when China's former
world champion and Olympic gold medalist Fu Mingxia won the women'
s platform diving and Vadim Gouzait of Ukraine got the men's sabre
title by beating Russian Stanislav Pozniakov to second.
</P>
<P>
In the men's volleyball competitions, Russia, Italy, Slovakia,
the United States and Germany recorded straight-set victories over
Estonia, Norway, Lithuania, Greece and Lebanon respectively, while
Sweden, Yugoslavia and Belgium were protracted to their full
matches before their respective victories over Mexico, Canada and
China.
</P>
<P>
Poland, South Korea, Japan and Spain won over their respective
rivals Turkey, Australia, the Netherlands and Brazil, losing only
one set.
</P>
<P>
The men's basketball also had a busy schedule as Ireland,
Greece, the Netherlands, Finland, Russia, Mexico, the Czech
Republic, Yugoslavia, the United States, Spain and Brazil all won
over their opponents.
</P>
<P>
The women's basketball competitions witnessed the most lop-
sided win as China beat South Africa 122-30, while Chinese Taipei
edged Brazil 81-80.
</P>
<P>
In other women division, Canada, Russia, Brazil, Ukraine,
Lithuania and Mexico came out the winners of the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
