<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Declares State of Emergency to Fight Dengue Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican Health Ministry
declared on Wednesday a state of emergency in Puerto Limon, on the
Caribbean coast, in a fight against a new outbreak of Dengue fever
affecting the region.
</P>
<P>
Six cases of hemorrhage dengue were registered in the region
last month, and 48 cases of the classic dengue over the last four
days, which alarmed the authorities, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is an endemic in the country. It is not a killer in its
classic form. However, the second contraction of the disease may
cause dengue hemorrhage, which is more dangerous to people's life.
</P>
<P>
To combat the outbreak of the disease, the ministry has taken
some preventative measures, such as the elimination of the
mosquito hatcheries, which are found in stagnant fresh water, by
fumigation campaigns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
