<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Results on Current Account in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The deficit of the Latin
American current account will drop this year in comparison with
1998, which is "good news" for the region, says the monthly
periodical "Latinwatch".
</P>
<P>
The publication, edited by Banco Bilbao Viscaya (BBV), a
financial society from Spain with widespread presence in the
region, said that the deficit may stay at 3.6 percent of the Gross
Domestic Product (GDP), compared with 4.5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Latinwatch foresees the growth of exports next year, "if the
internal demand" is reactive.
</P>
<P>
On the theme of exports, the analysts predict that there may be
a rise towards the end of the year, depending on the economic
recuperation of each country.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the commercial balance of Latin America
has performed well over the last few months, but still has to face
some challenges.
</P>
<P>
The financial institution estimates that it will be necessary
to recuperate exports over next year, to avoid problems caused by
the restrictions on the balance of payments.
</P>
<P>
As a stimulant to this process, the BBV said that it would be
desirable to rise the international prices of raw materials, of
which only petroleum has registered an increase.
</P>
<P>
It also recommends the application of macro and micro-economics,
which assure an adequate exchange rate on the long term, in
addition to well planned strategies for the promotion of exports
from the Latin American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
