<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ericsson CEO Resigns Amid Board Dissatisfaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sven-Chister Nilsson, chief
executive officer and president of Sweden's telecom equipment
maker L.M. Ericsson, resigned Wednesday amid board dissatisfaction
with his performance.
</P>
<P>
His job was split between two other Ericsson veterans. Lars
Ramqvist, chairman of the board, was named CEO and Kurt Hellstroem,
executive vice president-Asia Pacific, was appointed president.
</P>
<P>
Ramqvist told a press conference here that the board move was
prompted by dissatisfaction at Nilsson's slow implementation of
last year's decision to streamline the group and cut expenses.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the board of directors, driven by sliding profits,
decided to cut 11,000 employees worldwide. The figure was later
raised to 14,000. However, the downsizing plan was only met
halfway to date.
</P>
<P>
Ramqvist said the board was also "dissatisfied" with Nilsson's
lack of strong and effective measures to come up with new products,
which affected the company's profitability.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson's leadership shake-up led its shares on Stockholm's
exchange to drop by about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ericsson is Sweden's biggest company and the world's third
largest mobile phone maker. It has more than 100,000 employees in
140 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
