<HEADLINE> Indonesia Supplies 30 Pct of World's Pepper Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- In the last 10 years, Indonesia
supplied the world market with some 41,000 tons of black and white
pepper each year, accounting for 30 percent of the world's
consumption of the commodity, an official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
International Trade Director General Hartanto Rekso Dipoetro
said in Bandar Lampung, capital of Lampung province, that Lampung
was Indonesia's main black pepper producer and major foreign
exchange contributor to the state from the export of the
commodity.
</P>
<P>
In the last 10 years, Lampung was known for its specific black
pepper called "Lampung Black Pepper," Hartanto was quoted by
Antara News Agency Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lampung's black pepper exports in 1998 reached 23,000 tons
worth 100.3 million U.S. dollars, but only 11,288 tons worth 41.2
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May 1999 period Lampung has exported 2,365 tons
of black pepper.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the world's pepper consumption has now
reached an average of 120,000 tons per year, with Indonesia
supplying 41,000 tons each year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is the world's top producer of white pepper and ranks
the second in black pepper production after India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
