<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba's Suit Against U.S., Most Important Civil Procedure: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Justice Minister Roberto Diaz
said on Wednesday that Cuba's recent lawsuit against the United
States was the most important civil procedure in the country over
the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Diaz said the legal procedure had "a tremendous impact" because
the suit covers forty years of U.S. aggression against Cuba, which
can in no way be seen as an isolated event.
</P>
<P>
The minister is referring to the recently declassified
documents of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), which are
being used in the trial by four lawyers from eight Cuban plaintiff
social organizations, which plan to call witness and victims and
file documentary evidence to show how the U.S. policies have
damaged Cuban society over a period of four decades.
</P>
<P>
Diaz said the U.S. government had cheated international public
opinion throughout all these years and these documents proved it.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit, filed here in late May, requested 181 billion
dollars in compensatory and punitive damages from the U.S. for the
deaths of 3,478 Cubans and the permanent physical damage caused to
2,099 more people in a wide variety of acts ranging from the Bay
of Pigs invasion in the early 1961 to the bombing of Havana hotels
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The hearing of the procedure, starting on Monday will end in 30
working days, throughout which U.S. lawyer William Schaap, who has
filed various suits against the CIA, will be present as a private
observer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
