<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Coffee Production to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANIERO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide coffee production
for the 1999-2000 season is expected to contract by 1.8 percent in
the aftermath of a possible fall in Brazil's harvest, Brazilian
producers said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 104.16 million sacks (of 60 kilograms) of coffee are
expected to be harvested from this season worldwide, and the
predicted harvest for the next season is 102.86 million sacks, the
producers said.
</P>
<P>
The production of the robust variety of coffee beans, used
principally for the production of soluble coffee, will in the next
harvest amount to 36.3 million sacks, a 12.5-percent rise over the
previous season.
</P>
<P>
However, the global harvest of the Arabic variety, considered
to be milder, will drop by 8.3 percent, from 71.998 million sacks
to 66.3 million sacks, according to the producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
