<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia's Interest Rate Drops to 17.15 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The benchmark interest rate of Bank
Indonesia one-month promissory notes (SBI) dropped to 17.15
percent compared to 18.48 percent a week ago.
</P>
<P>
According to a central bank press release, quoted by national
newspapers Thursday, the decline in the benchmark rate was in line
with Bank Indonesia's plan to continue relaxing monetary
conditions over the next few months, with the hope of seeing the
rate fall to below 15 percent at year-end.
</P>
<P>
"The improving monetary condition is expected to provide
positive sentiment to the process of sustainable economic
recovery," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark rate of SBI hovered around 35 percent earlier
this year, and around 70 percent last August.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia Governor Syahril Sabirin said the central bank
would allow a further drop in interest rates on the back of
expectations of low inflation and a stronger rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah managed to strengthen to 6,700 rupiah per U.S.
dollar, compared to more than 14,000 rupiah last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in March, April, May and June was 0.18 percent, 0.68
percent, 0.28 percent and 0.34 percent respectively, bringing the
cumulative inflation in the first semester of this year to 2.73
percent compared to 46.55 percent in the corresponding period last
year.
</P>
<P>
"We expect inflation to remain low this month," Sabirin was
quoted by The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin was confident that inflation for the whole year would
be in the single digits, lower than earlier projections of between
10 percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, President B.J. Habibie seemed impatient to see the
lower rates translated into cheaper credits to businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The president has instructed the finance minister to study why
bank lending rates remain so high," Minister of Information
Muhammad Yunus said after a limited Cabinet meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bank lending interest rates are currently hovering at about 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post quoted analysts as saying that domestic banks
need more time to adjust their lending rates to the current lower
interest rate environment.
</P>
<P>
They said banks could not be expected to resume significant
lending in the near future, as banks were only now recovering from
the economic onslaught. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
