<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Stability Plan to Come out at Month End: Solana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 7 (Xinhua) -- NATO General-Secretary Javier
Solana announced here Wednesday that a stability plan for the
Balkans will be unveiled at the end of this month, with its
implementation guaranteed jointly by the military bloc, the United
Nations, the World Bank and the Organization for Security and Co-
operation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Solana, who made the announcement in talks with Romanian Prime
Minister Radu Vasile, assured that the plan, which covers
political, economic and security sectors, will turn a new leaf in
the history of the crisis-ridden region.
</P>
<P>
The plan, worked out by western powers and Russia at their
Cologne summit at the end of last month, is designed to help
Balkan countries with economic reconstruction and stabilization.
</P>
<P>
Realization of stability in Eastern and Southern Europe is of
great significance for the Balkan countries and Europe as a whole
to smoothly step into the 21st century, said the NATO chief.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who arrived here Wednesday night for a brief visit to
Romania, will exchange views with Romanian leaders on issues
concerning the current situation in the Balkans after the end of
the 78-day NATO pounding of Yugoslavia and Romania's NATO
membership.
</P>
<P>
He thanked Romania for its support for the alliance's military
operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Solana is the second western official to visit this country
since the end of the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia. U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright paid a three-hour visit on
June 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
