<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: EU, U.S. Row Over Global Competition Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission's plans
for establishing worldwide competition rules have been criticized
by the United States. The row between the European Union (EU) and
the United States focused on whether the World Trade Organization
(WTO) should have its own power to enforce global competition law
to prevent monopolies at a time when trade barriers are coming
down.
</P>
<P>
Leon Brittan, the EU commissioner for trade, who presented the
EU executive's competition plans, suggested that WTO members agree
to enact anti-trust laws and create agencies to enforce them,
according to the July 7 issue of the European Report, a
fortnightly journal of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The EU and U.S. widely differed over whether the anti-trust
issue should be put on the agenda of the WTO's Seattle talks in
November. At a conference in Paris last week hosted by the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), U.S.
Assistant Attorney-General Joel Klein said it was "entirely too
early" to talk about granting WTO the powers to enforce
competition laws because the body had no real experience with the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The senior U.S. official said Brittan's proposal was "a bad
idea" because any WTO negotiations "must build on experience and
commitment, not on hopes and vague concepts."
</P>
<P>
"WTO antitrust rules would be useless, pernicious, or both, and
would serve only to politicize the long-term future of
international antitrust enforcement," he told the OECD meeting
while calling for an overall program involving expanded and
deepened cooperative enforcement efforts on a bilateral basis.
</P>
<P>
However, Brittan said that bilateral coordination of procedures
was not sufficient if national laws were not designed to address
market access issues which foreign firms might face.
</P>
<P>
"These problems can only be resolved if countries around the
world enact sound competition principles and enforce them
effectively," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, as government restrictions to trade are progressively
reduced, there is increased concern that the benefits of trade
liberalization could be denied through anti-competitive business
practices with market foreclosure effects," he noted. He cited the
examples that national players were organizing themselves into
import or market-sharing cartels and exclusive distribution
practices were used to keep new competitors from abroad out of
their markets.
</P>
<P>
The chief EU trade negotiator emphasized that a global
framework was needed to cope with the increasing number of
antitrust cases that had an international dimension.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the American recourse to extraterritorial
application of its laws merely annoyed other countries rather than
got their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Experts worldwide are currently concerned over the issue of
monopoly, including the question of how to protect consumers from
enterprises that jack up prices higher than they would be if
competitive conditions prevailed.
</P>
<P>
"As official barriers to trade and investment fall", said
Donald Johnston, secretary-general of the OECD, companies have "
greater incentives to engage in anti-competitive conduct to
protect markets."
</P>
<P>
"Anti-competitive practices are not only detrimental to the
welfare of the country where they take place but are a matter of
legitimate concern to other trading partners," Brittan pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between the EU and the U.S. shows that monopoly is
still a key threat to world trade, even though all the 135 WTO
members, half of which have competition laws, are pushing ahead
with world trade liberalization which promotes business
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
