<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Sell Fusion Lab to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada is negotiating with Iran on
the selling of Canada's fusion research and nuclear reactor
technology program.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Center for Fusion Magnetics confirmed Wednesday
that the talks with Iran are entering into final stages.
</P>
<P>
"We're selling for 10 cents on a dollar or something like that,
" said the center sources.
</P>
<P>
The program has cost an estimated 250 million Canadian dollars
(about 170 million U.S. dollars) after 15 years of research and
development.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Center for Fusion Magnetics is a Montreal-based
research agency in charge of the fusion program, which is funded
by Ottawa's Atomic Energy of Canada Limited and by Hydro Quebec.
</P>
<P>
The center was given a final lump sum of 19 million Canadian
dollars (about 12.92 million U.S. dollars) in 1997 by Ottawa to
wind up operations after Atomic Energy decided to just concentrate
research on the Candu fission reactor.
</P>
<P>
As part of the deal, several Canadian scientists would work
with the Iranian government as consultants, the center sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The fusion reactor, called Takomak, is one of only 25 in the
world. The deal, if struck, would mark the end of Canada's
participation in the international quest for fusion, which many
scientists see as the energy source of the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Crackdown on Dereliction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's prosecutors have pledged to
keep up their efforts to crack down on official dereliction and
violation of personal and democratic rights, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Such crimes still present a serious problem, and remain at the
center of public complaints," Zhao Hong, deputy procurator-general
of the Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP), was quoted by the
newspaper as saying during a recent forum on procuratorial work.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the SPP, China's highest prosecuting organ,
indicate that, during the first five months of this year,
prosecutors put nearly 1,500 cases on file for investigation and
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
There were 174 cases of abuse of power, 451 cases of
dereliction of duty and 476 cases of violation of the citizens'
personal and democratic rights.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2,000 suspects were arrested between January and May,
including 42 leading officials of or above the county level.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors' efforts have recouped more than 23 million yuan (
about 2.8 million U.S. dollars) worth of losses, according to SPP.
</P>
<P>
In January, official corruption led to the collapse of the
Rainbow Bridge in Qijiang County in southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality, claiming 40 lives. Zhang Kaike, former Party
secretary of the county, was brought to court this week.
</P>
<P>
A heavy blow should be rendered against the abuse of power and
dereliction of government officials, which bring great losses of
life and property to the public, said Zhao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
