<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Guerrouj Shatters Mile World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj broke the
men's mile world record when he clocked three minutes 43.13
seconds at the second IAAF Golden League meeting of the season
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Guerrouj, who broke the 1,500 meters world mark on the same
track last year, was chased all the way by Kenya's Noah Ngeny in
the last lap and crossed the finish line just a few strides ahead
of his closest rival.
</P>
<P>
The Moroccan slimmed 1.26 seconds off the previous mark of 3:44.
39, which was set by Algeria's Noureddine Morceli in Rieti, Italy
in September 1993. Ngeny also finished inside the old record time
in 3:43.40.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Maurice Greene equaled the third-fastest
men's 100 meters of all time when he won easily in 9.85 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The American, who set a world record of 9.79 seconds in Athens
last month, got a perfect start and was two strides ahead of his
rivals at halfway before storming home for a comfortable win.
</P>
<P>
The performance equaled the time clocked by compatriot Leroy
Burrell when he set a previous world mark in Lausanne in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
That record stood for two years before Canada's Donovan Bailey
ran the second fastest time in history of 9.84 when he won the
Olympic final at the 1996 Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
Michael Johnson, Olympic champion over 200 and 400 meters, won
the 200m in 19.93 seconds. Obadele Thompson of Barbados powered
through in the last five meters to take second on the line in 20.
12, ahead of world champion Ato Boldon who was third in 20.14.
</P>
<P>
World sprint champion Marion Jones won the 200 meters in 22.19
to stay in the hunt for a share of the Golden League jackpot of
one million U.S. dollars to be awarded to athletes who win
specific events at all seven meetings in the lucrative series.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Wilson Kipketer of Kenya claimed victory in
the 800 meters in 1:42.79 to stay in contention for the cash.
</P>
<P>
A total of seven athletes remain in contention for the jackpot
with five meetings to come in Paris, Monaco, Zurich, Brussels and
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Jones and Kipketer, other Golden League
victories came from American Allen Johnson in men's 110m hurdles,
Kenyan Bernard Barmasai in steeplechase, American Erick Walder in
men's long jump, Russia's Svetlana Masterkova in women's 800m and
Romania's Gabriela Szabo in women's 3,000m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Foreign Ministry on Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been pursuing a foreign
policy of "positive neutrality" since it regained its independence
on January 4, 1948 and has declared that its policy would best
serve the national interests as well as the interests of world
peace and security by standing on the side of justice in
international issues and by refusing to be aligned with any group
or power bloc.
</P>
<P>
"It is a policy which remains valid today," the Myanmar Foreign
Ministry said in its currently published "Diplomatic Handbook"
which aims to introduce Myanmar's diplomacy to the world.
</P>
<P>
The handbook stresses that Myanmar's basic principles of its
foreign policy are:
</P>
<P>
-- respect for equality among peoples and among nations and the
upholding of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence;
</P>
<P>
-- taking a non-aligned, independent and just stand in
international issues;
</P>
<P>
-- maintaining friendly relations with all nations, and
good-neighborly relations with neighboring states;
</P>
<P>
-- the continued support of, and active participation in the
U.N. and its subsidiary organizations;
</P>
<P>
-- the pursuance of mutually beneficial bilateral and
multilateral cooperation programs;
</P>
<P>
-- regional consultation and beneficial cooperation in regional
economic and social affairs;
</P>
<P>
-- active participation in the maintenance of world peace and
security, opposition to imperialism, colonialism, neo-colonialism,
interference, aggression and domination of one state by another
and the creation of equitable economic conditions;
</P>
<P>
-- and acceptance of foreign aid which is beneficial to
national development, provided there are no strings attached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
