<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China City Renovates Famous Prison for War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hushun city in northeast China
's Liaoning province plans to inject six million yuan into
renovating a famous prison for war criminals which was once
resided by the last Chinese emperor Puyi.
</P>
<P>
Renovation work started as early as last February, and the site
is expected to reopen to public on September 8.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1950, the prison was a place to reform war criminals
including Puyi, Japanese army officers captured in their invasion
of China, and some generals of the Kuomintang captured during the
liberation war.
</P>
<P>
The site was transformed into a base for education in
patriotism and for tourism destination in late 1960s. However,
serious damages were reported in its buildings and related
facilities due to lack of repair and reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
After the renovation project, the site is expected to be
divided into three special areas including two exhibition halls
and a collection of sites including the abode, bathroom and a
barber's place of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Also, former exhibits will be re-arranged and new exhibits will
be added including some photos, historical documents, and some
articles once used by the war criminals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Imposes Tariffs on Australia, New Zealand Lamb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton Administration moved
on Wednesday to limit lamb imports and imposed penalty tariffs
after U.S. ranchers complained that Australia and New Zealand lamb
flooding into the country was driving them out of business.
</P>
<P>
Beginning July 22, a 9 percent tariff will be imposed on the
first 31,851 metric tons, the amount of lamb imported last year.
Shipments above that level will carry a 40 percent tariff, the
White House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This package has been carefully designed to help achieve
sustained competitiveness for the U.S. industry and is fully
consistent with our international trade obligations," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
American ranchers had complained that current tariffs of less
than 1 percent were too low to protect them from foreign
competitors flooding the U.S. market with their exports.
</P>
<P>
Australia and New Zealand account for 95 percent of the lamb
imported into the United States. Importers have contended that
higher tariffs would violate World Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
Under this three-year tariff rising program, the tariffs set on
lamb import below the quota level will be cut to 6 percent in the
second year and 3 percent in the third year. The quota level will
increase by an additional 857 metric tons in the second and third
years.
</P>
<P>
Lamb imported above the quota amount will be subject to a 40
percent tariff in the first year, dropping to 32 percent in the
second year and 24 percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
The program also includes 100 million U.S. dollars of
government aid to help the U.S. lamb industry develop methods to
reduce operating costs so that U.S. lamb will be in a better
position to compete after the program ends.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government acted after the U.S. International Trade
Commission ruled in a trade case filed by the American Sheep
Industry Association and other industry groups that U.S. producers
were being harmed by a surge in lamb imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
