<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Additional Fund for SEA Games Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's 20th Southeast Asian
SEA) Games team may feel much relieved at the news that the
National Sports Council (KONI) chairman Wismoyo Arismunandar had
approved an additional sum of two billion rupiah (298,500 U.S.
dollars) for the team's trip to and competitions at the Games.
</P>
<P>
Mochammad Hindarto, a KONI official in charge of athletes
development program, said that so far KONI had collected 12
billion rupiah for the contingent's transportation and
accommodation during the biennial event August 7-15 in Brunei
Darussalam.
</P>
<P>
The National Development and Planning Board and the Gelora
Senayan Management Board have provided 5.5 billion rupiah and 4.5
billion rupiah respectively.
</P>
<P>
"But the 10 billion rupiah budget was not enough as we still
needed to add 500 million rupiah. We're lucky that Wismoyo
understood our need," Hindarto said, adding that the money could
be used to buy sports equipment to support athletes performances
in the event.
</P>
<P>
The additional sum of money was part of a seven billion rupiah
donation from the State Enterprises annual profits, according to
the newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
But Wismoyo was not happy with the medal targets for the SEA
Games set by the country's sports organizations.
</P>
<P>
SEA Games training executive director Imron Z.S. quoted Wismoyo
's statement saying the organizations were intentionally keeping a
low-key profile.
</P>
<P>
"In sports, we have to make the right estimations. If they can
win seven golds, please say seven and no less. Don't say they are
afraid of over-targeting. We have to evaluate right or we miss
targets. We need to know our rivals' strength. We must remember
that the SEA Games is a stepping stone to bigger events such as
the Asian Games and the Olympics," Imron said.
</P>
<P>
Imron was referring to the Badminton Association of Indonesia,
which opted to send second stringers because the top players were
focused on qualifying for the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Imron named karate, pencak silat and taekwondo as other sports
expected to win more medals than targeted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
