<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Leaves Nepal for Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Bandaranaike Kumaratunga left here Thursday for Bhutan after
completing her four-day state visit to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
She was seen off at the airport by Nepali King Birendra, Queen
Aishwarya and Prime Minister Krishna Prasad Bhattarai.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga described as "friendly and fruitful" her talks with
King Birendra, Prime Minister Bhattarai and other Nepali
officials. This is her first ever visit to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
During her visit here, Sri Lanka and Nepal signed two
agreements on avoidance of double taxation and boosting cultural
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
As current chairperson of the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Kumaratunga availed
her of the opportunity to call for closer people-to-people
contacts and free trade in the region. She also visited the
Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan delegation described their visit to Bhutan as a
bilateral one as well. But it was regarded that President
Kumaratunga is touring Nepal and Bhutan also in her capacity as
the SAARC chairperson.
</P>
<P>
It is a practice for the SAARC chairperson to visit all the
other six SAARC capitals before the next summit opens.
</P>
<P>
The 11th SAARC summit is scheduled to be held in Kathmandu in
November this year.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
