<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Angers at U.S. Restrictions on Lamb Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian acting Prime Minister
Tim Fischer described Thursday the U.S. decision to limit
Australian lamb exports as "doing something very wrong."
</P>
<P>
"This is not only outrageous, not only unwarranted, it is
actually reckless by the U.S.," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration decided Wednesday to impose a quota
of 31,851 metric tons on lamb imports from Australia, New Zealand
and some other countries, which would increase over three years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a tariff of 9 percent for those within the quota was
claimed and a punishing rate for outside that quota was up to 40
percent. Both of the rates would reduce in three years.
</P>
<P>
Fischer was quoted by an AAP report as saying that "ultimately
it is a case of might, the largest economy in the world, the most
powerful political unit in the world doing something very wrong
and not what is right."
</P>
<P>
Australia exported about 66 million U.S. dollars worth of lamb
to the United States each year and the newly introduced U.S.
restrictions will cost each lamb producer in Australia who
exported to the United States about 3.3 U.S. dollars a head and
cost this country about 6.6 million to 9.9 million U.S. dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said that he would direct the Australian
representatives in Geneva to take step in the World Trade
Organization, seeking immediate consultations with the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
