<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Brazil Reach Agreement on Limiting Brazilian Steel Shipments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Brazil
have reached agreement on voluntarily reducing hot-rolled carbon
steel shipments by Brazil to the United States to avert punitive
tariffs against the Brazilian steel producers, U.S. officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil also agreed to quotas on the core steel product and to
minimum prices set above those currently prevailing in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached hours before a midnight Tuesday deadline
would suspend the U.S. industry's tariff petitions. Without the
agreement, Brazilian producers would have faced tariffs ranging
from 48-53 percent.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary William Daley said the restrictions on
Brazil would eliminate the ability of Brazilian firms to sell
steel in the United States at cut-rate prices.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. steel industry sought tariffs against Brazil and other
countries to combat a flood of low-priced imports, which the
industry blames for thousands of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. International Trade Commission, in a 5-1
ruling, approved tariffs of as much as 71 percent on one type of
stainless steel from France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Mexico, South
Korea, Britain and Taiwan of China.
</P>
<P>
The product, sold in flat sheets rolled up like carpet, is used
in kitchen sinks, dishwashers and other appliances.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements announced Wednesday, Brazil will reduce
hot-rolled shipments by about 28 percent and accept 12-month
quotas of 295,000 metric tons. No shipment will be allowed before
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian producers also agreed to charge U.S. customers of
that product at least 327 U.S. dollar per metric ton, which is
above the prevailing U.S. price of about 300 dollars. The
Brazilian floor price would be adjusted quarterly if the U.S.
market price increases.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. industry officials have complained their legal rights
to seek tariffs are compromised through such deals, and major
steel companies and the United Steelworkers of America threatened
legal challenges Wednesday to the agreements. Other companies
supported the agreements after changes were made to establish the
minimum price.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department, in announcing the agreements,
concluded that Brazil unlawfully subsidized its producers and that
the producers unfairly dumped hot-rolled steel in the United
States at prices below production costs and home-market prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
