<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) on
Wednesday approved a loan of 4.12 billion U.S. dollars for Mexico
that is part of a larger package of credits designed to help the
country avert economic turmoil during next year's presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
An IMF spokesman said the loan will be disbursed in seven
installments over a 17-month period, provided that Mexico sticks
to terms of an economic program agreed with the IMF. (IMF-Mexico)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- U.S. chief executives' confidence in the nation's
economy increased by 10 points in the second quarter, the
Conference Board, a U.S. prominent research group, said in a
report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Measure of Business Confidence in the
second quarter jumped to 56 from the previous quarter's reading of
46. A reading of more than 50 points reflects more positive than
negative responses. (US-C. Board-CEO Confidence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The Italian automaker Fiat and the Japanese vehicle
company Mitsubishi on Wednesday struck a deal for jointly
producing a new four-wheel-drive sports utility car in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Fiat, which will invest 250 billion lire (about 135 million U.S.
dollars) in the project, will be responsible for the car's design
and styling, while Mitsubishi, with its expertise in four-wheel-
drive vehicles, will produce the chassis and engine. (Italy-Fiat-
Mitsubishi)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- In the last 10 years, Indonesia supplied the world
market with some 41,000 tons of black and white pepper each year,
accounting for 30 percent of the world's consumption of the
commodity, an official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
International Trade Director General Hartanto Rekso Dipoetro
said in Bandar Lampung, capital of Lampung province, that Lampung
was Indonesia's main black pepper producer and major foreign
exchange contributor to the state from the export of the commodity.
(Indonesia-Pepper)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- The Ukrainian government plans to increase the
proportion of coal and uranium in its energy sources and reduce
that of natural gas, which is largely imported, First Deputy Prime
Minister Vladimir Kuratchenko said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a meeting on the country's power sources held by
the presidium of the Ukrainian Academy of Sciences, Kuratchenko
said that under the economic plan for the next decade, coal is to
provide for 50 percent of Ukraine's energy while uranium, 40
percent, within the coming few years. (Ukraine-Energy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANIERO -- Worldwide coffee production for the 1999-2000
season is expected to contract by 1.8 percent in the aftermath of
a possible fall in Brazil's harvest, Brazilian producers said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 104.16 million sacks (of 60 kilograms) of coffee are
expected to be harvested from this season worldwide, and the
predicted harvest for the next season is 102.86 million sacks, the
producers said. (Brazil-Coffee Production)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Clinton Administration moved on Wednesday to
limit lamb imports and imposed penalty tariffs after U.S. ranchers
complained that Australia and New Zealand lamb flooding into the
country was driving them out of business.
</P>
<P>
Beginning July 22, a 9 percent tariff will be imposed on the
first 31,851 metric tons, the amount of lamb imported last year.
Shipments above that level will carry a 40 percent tariff, the
White House said in a statement. (US-Lamb Tariff)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australian acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer on
Thursday described the U.S. decision to limit Australian lamb
exports as "doing something very wrong."
</P>
<P>
"This is not only outrageous, not only unwarranted, it is
actually reckless by the U.S.," he said. (Australia-US-Lamb
Export) 
</P>
