<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Study May Unlock Mystery of Alzheimer's Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A form of the very peptide that
initiates accumulation of amyloid plaques in the brains of people
with Alzheimer's disease may someday be used as a treatment for
this devastating ailment.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the findings, the U.S. Alzheimer's Association
said Wednesday that this is an exciting and encouraging study for
the prevention and possible treating of Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by researchers at Elan Corporation, a
leading worldwide specialty pharmaceutical company headquartered
in Ireland. Their findings are to be published in the July 8 issue
of the journal Nature, the association said.
</P>
<P>
For many years, the association said, scientists have
hypothesized that the presence of amyloid plaques causes cell
death and leads to a decline in a person's cognitive functions.
Scientists now have an opportunity to test this theory and begin
unlocking the mystery behind this disease.
</P>
<P>
The researchers immunized a group of transgenic mice -- mice
genetically engineered to develop Alzheimer's disease pathology
similar to that which is seen in humans -- with a form of the beta
amyloid peptide called AN-1792. The results of their study were
based on two separate experiments.
</P>
<P>
In the first experiment, the mice were immunized at an age well
before they developed amyloid plaque and associated brain damage.
After 13 months, the researchers compared the brains of the
immunized mice to three control groups of mice that were left
untreated. The group treated with AN-1792 showed virtually no
detectable amyloid deposits in their brains, while the three
control groups showed no reduction in the progressive deposition
of plaques. The researchers concluded that these results raise the
possibility of immunization with AN-1792 as a prevention against
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
In the second experiment, mature mice, which already exhibited
substantial Alzheimer's pathology, were treated with AN-1792 for a
period of seven months. The researchers found that the level of
plaques and related neuropathology was both halted and reduced in
the treated mice, suggesting that this treatment may clear plaques
even after they have formed.
</P>
<P>
Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, degenerative disease of
the brain. It primarily afflicts older people and begins with
symptoms such as simple confusion and forgetfulness. Ultimately,
the disease leads to profound dementia. Approximately four million
people in the United States have Alzheimer's disease. It affects
one person in 10 over age 65, and almost half of all persons over
age 85. According to the Alzheimer's Association, the overall cost
of Alzheimer's disease to families and society in the U.S. is
estimated at 80-100 billion U.S. dollars annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
