<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export earnings fell
short of the target in the first 11 months of the just-ended
1998-99 fiscal year, as major export sectors failed to earn as
much money as previously expected, The Daily Star Business
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The country's export fetched 4,761.91 million U.S. dollars from
July 1998 to May this year, some 7.7 percent short of the targeted
5,160.81 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total export earnings, however, exceeded the figure of the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal by 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Except the garments sector, all the major export sectors,
including knitwear, frozen food, leather, raw jute and jute goods,
agriculture products, petroleum by-products and chemical products,
could not achieve their targets during the July 1998-May 1999
period.
</P>
<P>
Export of manufacturing products amounted to 4,380.63 million
dollars, about 5.4 percent behind the target, while earnings from
primary products exports stood at 381.28 million dollars, some
28.3 percent short of the target of 531.66 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The garments sector earned 2,653.27 million dollars, 5 percent
higher than the target.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from knitwear and frozen food stood at 935.74
million dollars and 245.93 million dollars respectively, 13.34
percent and 23.35 percent below their respective target.
</P>
<P>
Jute goods exports earned 275 million dollars, 3.7 percent
short of target, while leather export made 151 million dollars
against the 206-million-dollar target.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by the 1997-98 fiscal year's export growth of 16.8
percent, the Bangladeshi government set an export target for the
1998-99 fiscal at 5.8 billion dollars which was later revised to
5.63 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
