<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Renovates Famous Prison for War Criminals (RPT) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Fushun city in northeast China
's Liaoning province plans to inject six million yuan into
renovating a famous prison for war criminals which was once
resided by the last Chinese emperor Puyi.
</P>
<P>
Renovation work started as early as last February, and the site
is expected to reopen to public on September 8.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1950, the prison was a place to reform war criminals
including Puyi, Japanese army officers captured in their invasion
of China, and some generals of the Kuomintang captured during the
liberation war.
</P>
<P>
The site was transformed into a base for education in
patriotism and for tourism destination in late 1960s. However,
serious damages were reported in its buildings and related
facilities due to lack of repair and reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
After the renovation project, the site is expected to be
divided into three special areas including two exhibition halls
and a collection of sites including the abode, bathroom and a
barber's place of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Also, former exhibits will be re-arranged and new exhibits will
be added including some photos, historical documents, and some
articles once used by the war criminals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
