<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Starts to Sanitize Nigeria's Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The head of Nigeria's Petroleum
Distribution Company has been relieved of his job as part of an
ongoing effort to sanitize the country's oil industry, sources at
the headquarters of the nation's oil corporation said.
</P>
<P>
P. C. Okonkwo, head of the petroleum products marketing
company, a subsidiary of the National Petroleum Corporation,
received his letter of retirement Tuesday, after a meeting
attended by Jackson Gaius-Obaseki, the head of the corporation,
and senior officials of its subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
Other top officials of subsidiaries, including those in the gas
sector, are feared to have been affected in the latest retirement,
which is coming barely a week after 71 officials responsible for
the country's depots for refined petroleum were retired.
</P>
<P>
Inefficiency and corruption in critical segments of the
corporation has been blamed for the poor performance of the
Nigerian oil industry, including the recurring fuel scarcity that
recently characterized the country's experience.
</P>
<P>
The new Nigerian government, which came into office on May 29,
has recently focused on the nation's oil industry, which provides
about 95 percent of the income for this west African country.
</P>
<P>
Recently, it cancelled 41 licences granted by the former
military regime to companies for the sale of the country's crude
oil, followed later with the cancellation of 16 oil prospecting
licences granted between March and May.
</P>
<P>
Gaius-Obaseki, head of the petroleum corporation, recently
pledged to revitalize the sector to restore the confidence of
Nigerians in the organization which came under severe criticism
during the regime of late Nigerian leader Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
A supplementary budget that would take care of the expenses in
the Nigeria-led west African peacekeeping force, ECOMOG, and
other developments, is being prepared by the Nigerian government
for submission to the country's legislature, the country's
spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Dapo Sarumi, Minister of Information, said ministries
have been directed to forward their supplementary budgets to the
president by July 15.
</P>
<P>
He said the president conveyed the directive during Wednesday's
federal executive council meeting, the second since the ministers
were sworn in last week.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said the supplementary budget would enable
the government, which is battling to contain a deficit estimated
at 300 billion naira (about 3 billion US dollars) in May, to take
care of the ministries created by the new administration.
</P>
<P>
The council, consisting of ministers and key officials of the
government, also approved the revised civil service rules and
financial regulations for the country's 600,000 strong public
sector.
</P>
<P>
"The intention is to ensure that public officers are aware of
the rules so that they (the rules) are not exploited by some
officers to intimidate others," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rules provide a guideline for the conduct of public
officers and the expenditure of public funds, two areas that have
were fingered for the deterioration of the country's public
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
