<HEADLINE> S. Leonean President Urges National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- President Tejan Kabbah Wednesday
called on his fellow Sierra Leoneans to learn to "forgive and
forget" in rehabilitating the war-torn west African country, a
report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before signing the peace accord with the rebels in
Togolese capital Lome, the president introduced a mutilated woman
and a child to the audience, saying that they are the victims of
the war waged by the rebel Revolutionary United Front's forces.
</P>
<P>
Despite the atrocities made by the rebels, the Sierra Leonean
people should learn to "forgive and forget" and pool their efforts
in achieving a true national reconciliation, said Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The signing process began following Kabbah's speech.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Kabbah and rebel leader Foday Sankoh, presidents
of Nigeria, Liberia, Burkina Faso and Togo as well as
representatives of the U. N. and other international organizations
started signing their names on many places of the stacked
documents.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who led the rebels in fighting successive governments
since 1991 latter addressed the ceremony, and Togo's Foreign
minister Kokou Koffigoh, also a general coordinator of the
seven-week peace talks, would release a communique.
</P>
<P>
The accord, agreed to only on Wednesday morning, stipulates
that the rebels will be disarmed and share power with the elected
Kabbah administration by acquiring several ministerial posts in a
transitional government.
</P>
<P>
But the Nigeria-led west Africa peace-keeping force ECOMOG will
stay in Sierra Leone, according to the document, which was
formerly opposed by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Nigeria, Burkina Faso, Liberia and the host
country Togo were present at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit, called by Togolese President Gnassingbe
Eyadema, current Chairman of the Economic Community of the West
Africa States (ECOWAS), played an important role in removing the
final hurdles on the road to the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
All parties concerned, including Nigeria which has been leading
the ECOMOG in fighting the Sierra Leonean rebels and Liberia and
Burkina Faso which had been allegedly backing the rebels secretly,
were brought together to made a final push for a lasting peace in
the war-torn west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
