<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Bans Bulgarian Airline's Flights to Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has ordered Bulgaria's
Balkan Airline to stop its services to Beirut as of July 15 after
it sold most of its shares to an Israeli company.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star reported Thursday that Lebanese Civil Aviation
Director Faisal Mikdashi ordered the ban after Balkan Airlines,
which had made three flights a week to Beirut via Damascus, sold 75
percent of its shares to the Zeevi Group, an Israeli company.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which is occupying part of south Lebanon as a buffer
zone to protect its north, is officially at war with the country.
</P>
<P>
Mikdashi said that this is not a blanket ban and other
Bulgarian carriers may still fly into Beirut.
</P>
<P>
"Balkan Airline can be replaced by any other Bulgarian company
capable of implementing a deal on flights between Beirut and
Sofia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Balkan was one of the few airlines that flew into Beirut
during Lebanon's 1975-1990 civil war and together with Greece's
Olympic Airway, was the main carrier between Beirut and the Balkan.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Ambassador Nikolay Andreev in Beirut discussed the
ban with Lebanese Foreign Ministry's director-general Zafer
Hassan.
</P>
<P>
"This is a political issue for Lebanon and an economic issue
for Bulgaria," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
"My government is privatizing and the Israeli firm's offer was
the best bid tendered," he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that political and commercial ties between Lebanon
and Bulgaria will not be affected because of the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
