<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Thursday launched Cyberjaya, one of the world's
intelligent cities and the nerve center of his brainchild
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC).
</P>
<P>
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) is a 50 km by 15 km zone
stretching southward from Kuala Lumpur specially designated for
the development of high technology including computer and
information industries.
</P>
<P>
The MSC, created by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad in August
1996, covers an area of 750 square kilometers stretching from the
Kuala Lumpur city center southward to the new administrative
capital Putrajaya and the New Kuala Lumpur International Airport
in Sepang.
</P>
<P>
The new capital and the first city in the corridor, Cyberjaya,
are scheduled to be completed by 2015. Major cities in the
corridor will be connected to each other by high speed railway and
express highway.
</P>
<P>
The MSC, which observers say presents the cutting edge of
Malaysia's commitment to ensuring the country is not left behind
in the IT explosion and will become Malaysia's pride, has been
acknowledged by world computer experts as a major effort to
concentrate on IT development with definite objectives.
</P>
<P>
The MSC will cater for eight flagship applications: electronic
or "paperless" government, tele-medicine, research and
development, worldwide manufacturing web, borderless marketing
center, multimedia funds haven, the world's first multipurpose
smart card, and Smart Schools.
</P>
<P>
Part of the funds for these projects is provided by the
Malaysian government with the rest raised from private sectors,
especially foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
So far, 225 companies have been granted the MSC status, with
most of them being foreign companies based in Europe, the United
States, Canada and Japan and joint ventures between Malaysian
companies and foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
These companies which have obtained MSC status would invest a
total sum of more than 1 billion U.S. dollars over a five-year
period in various fields such as computer software,
telecommunications and electronic equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Leone to Move Forward with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The document, read by Togolese Foreign Minister Kokou Koffigoh
at the end of the prolonged event, declared the "immediate
release" of Sankoh, who had been on a parole from a death
sentence.
</P>
<P>
He would take a vice-president position ranking as the
chairmanship of the Commission for the Management of Strategic
Resources, National Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front (RUF), which took up arms
against successive governments since 1991, will be transformed
into a political party and secure a number of ministerial posts,
according to the document.
</P>
<P>
In exchange for the provisions in RUF's favor, the Nigeria-led
west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG will stay, contrary to the
rebels' previously insisted position.
</P>
<P>
For the issue of amnesty, a major concern for the RUF and a
controversy for the nation, the communique has only blurring
provisions. At one point, the document said amnesty will be
granted to the RUF combatants but at another it provides that
mechanisms would be reinforced to address the grievances of people
in respect of alleged violations of basic human rights
</P>
<P>
The issue, if not properly addressed, might be potentially
explosive, since the rebels in the bushes might simply refuse to
disarm for fear of reprisal and the long suffered civilians as
well as some officials of the Kabbah government may insist on
bringing some of them to justice.  Actually, the trouble has
already emerged when the United Nations immediately rejected the
amnesty provisions in the peace accord, despite its endorsement
of the agreement as a whole via its special representative Francis
Okelo in Lome, capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The rebels reportedly killed about 5,000 innocent civilians in
its January assault to Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, this
year. Recently, many international human rights groups have been
vehemently accusing the rebels of systematically killing thousands
of people, raping and mutilating many others in the their
decade-long war to gain power.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made Wednesday before signing the peace accord,
Kabbah called on his fellow Sierra Leoneans to learn to "forgive
and forget" to rehabilitate the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah will address Sierra Leone's parliament Thursday in a bid
to push through the peace accord. Skepticism, hesitation and
reluctance toward implementing the accord would be expected in his
government and country.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure many of you believe that the government has given
the RUF far too much already and the RUF has given very little or
nothing at all," Kabbah said before jetting off to Lome to attend
the mini-summit called by Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "I have no doubt you will agree with me after so
much pain and sufferings, after so much destruction of life and
property, we need to exercise patience and persevere in our search
for a lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Nigeria, Burkina Faso, Liberia and the host
country Togo attended the two-day regional summit culminating in
the signing of the peace agreement Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The mini-summit played an important role in removing the final
hurdles in the seven-week marathon peace talks in Lome.
</P>
<P>
All parties concerned, including Nigeria which has been leading
the ECOMOG in fighting the Sierra Leonean rebels, and Liberia and
Burkina Faso which had been allegedly backing the rebels
secretly, were brought together to make a final push for a lasting
peace in the war-torn west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
