<HEADLINE> Jordan Hopes Barak to Reinvigorate Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan hopes that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak would act swiftly and breathe new life into
the stagnant Middle East peace process, the semi-official Jordan
Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the formation of the new cabinet and its success
in securing a tangible majority in the Knesset (parliament) will
usher in a new era which will bring the peace process back on
track," Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel-Ilah Khatib was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has repeatedly called on Israel to resume peace talks
with the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon since Barak won the May
17 elections which brought down his hard-line predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu of the Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Israel's peace talks with the Arab neighbors remained mostly
deadlocked since Netanyahu came to power in 1996 due to his
uncompromising policies.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was sworn in as prime minister on Tuesday, is
expected to meet Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein before his
visit to the United States on July 16, Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1984, has
been a major peace broker in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
