<HEADLINE> Manila Ready to Evacuate Farmers Near Mayon Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is ready
to evacuate farmers who insist on returning to 6-kilometer danger
zone around Mayon once Alert Level 3 is imposed for the volcano, a
senior official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Gloria Arroyo, also secretary of the Department
of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD), told reporters that the
forced evacuation policy takes effect immediately when authorities
raise Mayon's alert level, which now stand at Level 2.
</P>
<P>
"As of now, no one lives in the imminent danger zone anymore.
The problem is the soil in that area is very fertile," Arroyo
said.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers are reportedly hesitant to leave the area because
of the fertility of the soil around the volcano.
</P>
<P>
Arroyo also reassured the public all government preparations
are in place if Mayon erupts.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology has
placed Mayon under watch since the volcano starting spewing smoke
on June 22.
</P>
<P>
It also raised Mayon's alert level to Level 2, which means an
explosion may happen in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
"While the volcano has not reached Alert Level 3, we are
concentrating on disaster preparedness, which includes the
stockpiling of goods," Arroyo said.
</P>
<P>
The DSWD regional director can buy rice, canned goods, clothes
and other commodities from the National Food Authority (NFA) once
the evacuation takes place, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The DSWD has also prepared ready-to-eat food good for at least
15,000 meals, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
