<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Starts Customs System in Member States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has implemented the automated system for
customs data and management computer program in 12 of its 21
member states with pre- installation having been completed in
three other states.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Thursday quoted senior trade sources at COMESA
headquarters in Lusaka as saying that the system is part of a
comprehensive program aimed at enhancing the mode of customs
clearance and trade statistics processing in COMESA member states
before the realization of the COMESA customs union treaty in 2004.
</P>
<P>
Those that have so far implemented the program are Burundi,
Comoros, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Madagascar,
Namibia, Rwanda, Sudan and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Others are Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, while pre-installation
inspections have been carried out in Kenya, Lesotho and Angola.
</P>
<P>
And system's implementation program is currently underway in
Malawi and Eritrea, Swaziland is expected to follow soon.
</P>
<P>
Although implementation of the program is one year behind
schedule, trade experts in COMESA are confident the program would
have been implemented by all member states before the October 2004
deadline for the COMESA union treaty, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
When fully operational, the national systems would be centrally
linked to the COMESA regional center where national data on trade
statistics would be analyzed and placed in a data bank for
accessing and use by stake- holders, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
