<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Suspends Sanctions on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has suspended the sanctions
imposed on Libya according to U.N. resolutions, the Cyprus News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken Wednesday at a cabinet meeting chaired
by President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
According to an official announcement, the Cypriot government,
falling in with the position of European Union, has not suspended
sanctions concerning exports of arms and military equipment.
</P>
<P>
It has also retained restrictions in the movement of
diplomatic personnel and a strict procedure in the issuing of
visas.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Security Council sanctions imposed on Libya since 1992 for
its alleged part in the bombing of a Pan AM airliner over
Lockerbie, were suspended in April after Tripoli surrendered two
suspects in the Lockerbie disaster to be tried in the Netherlands.
</P>
</TEXT>
