<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of the
diplomatic news released by Xinhua here today:
</P>
<P>
 Japanese PM Arrives for Official Visit
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi arrived in Beijing by
special plane this afternoon on an official visit as guest of
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
This is Obuchi's first visit to China since he became prime
minister. His over-100-member entourage includes Home Affairs
Minister Takeshi Noda, Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura, and other
senior officials as well as people from the business circle.
</P>
<P>
PNG Urged to Correct Erroneous Decision on PNG-Taiwan "
Diplomatic Ties"
</P>
<P>
A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman reiterated today that
China hopes the Papua New Guinean government would immediately
correct its erroneous decision of establishing "diplomatic ties"
with Taiwan so as to bring the relations between China and PNG
back onto the normal track.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue made the remark at a regular press
conference when asked to comment on the resignation of PNG Prime
Minister Bill Skate.
</P>
<P>
FM Spokeswoman on Newly-appointed U.S. Ambassador to China
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said this
afternoon that she "could hardly" comment on the newly-appointed U.
S. Ambassador to China because the United States has yet to give
formal message about this to China.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference, Zhang Qiyue said that the U.S.
Senate is discussing the appointment of Joseph Prueher, former
commander in chief of the U.S. forces in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
FM Spokeswoman on Japanese Prime Minister's Visit
</P>
<P>
China plans to exchange views with Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi on comprehensively implementing the consensus reached
by the two countries during Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state
visit to Japan, including establishing a hotline between the two
governments, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's official visit to China will be another important
contact between the two countries after Jiang's Japan visit last
year, spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said in response to a question at a
regular press conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
