<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China today demanded that the United States government stick to
its commitment that Tibet is a part of China and reject a proposal
in the House of Representatives to designate July 10 "World Tibet
Day."
</P>
<P>
Tibet is an inalienable part of Chinese territory and Tibetan
affairs are the internal affairs of China and no foreign country
has the right to interfere in them, said Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue at a press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
China, Kazakhstan Keen to Promote Ties
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, in talks today with Kazakh
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart Tokayev,
said that China places great importance on its relations with
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Tang and Tokayev expressed satisfaction with
the smooth development of bilateral ties. They agreed that the two
countries should increase mutually beneficial cooperation in all
areas, according to a Chinese foreign ministry official who
attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
Japanese PM: Visit a Show of Friendship
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said today that his three
day official visit demonstrates the friendly feelings of the
Japanese Government and people towards China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reception celebrating the inauguration of "The '
99 China-Japan Year of Cultural Friendship" activity only one and
a half hours after his arrival, the Prime Minister expressed
sincere pleasure over the visit at a time when China is preparing
major celebrations for the 50th anniversary of the founding of New
China and the 20th anniversary of the signing of the China-Japan
Cultural Exchange Agreement. 
</P>
