<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Thursday that
Moscow would follow a middle-of-the-road course when dealing with
the West, avoiding both direct confrontation and unquestioning
friendship.
</P>
<P>
In an address to military leaders in the Kremlin, Yeltsin said
Russia's relations with NATO and the United States "remain
delicate and difficult."
</P>
<P>
"We will not confront NATO directly, but we will not flirt
with them either," Yeltsin said, "We shall closely follow NATO's
moves and work out our tactics together."(Russia-Yeltsin-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said Thursday
that his three day official visit in China demonstrates the
friendly feelings of the Japanese Government and people towards
China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reception celebrating the inauguration of "The '
99 China-Japan Year of Cultural Friendship" activity only one and
a half hours after his arrival, the Prime Minister expressed
sincere pleasure over the visit at a time when China is preparing
major celebrations for the 50th anniversary of its founding and
the 20th anniversary of the signing of the China-Japan Cultural
Exchange Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Since the normalization of relations between Japan and China 27
years ago dialogue and communication have greatly increased," he
said, adding that while about to embrace the new century, the two
countries should further consolidate their mutual understanding
and trust, which were fostered over many years. (China-Japan-PM-
Reception)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The Indian Army has recaptured two peaks in the
Batalik sub-sector and one in the Drass sector of Kashmir, killing
92 enemy soldiers while losing 38 of its own men, Indian Army
sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Troops of 11 Gorkha Rifles and a Bihar Regiment Battalion
recaptured the two peaks after night-long fierce fighting in the
Batalik sub-sector in operations to clear the peaks, they said.
</P>
<P>
With reinforcements entering some areas, Pakistani troops
launched counterattack at four positions but were effectively
repulsed, they said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 634 Pakistani regulars have reportedly been killed
in Kargil while India has lost 321 men including 23 officers since
the Indian operation began on May 8.
</P>
<P>
The sources said there was no qualitative change on the ground
in Kargil after Sunday's meeting between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. Islamabad
showed "no signs" of abiding by its commitment to pull back its
troops and extremist elements from the Indian side of the Line of
Control (LOC), they said. (India-Kashmir-Peaks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
