<HEADLINE> Famine Threatens 1 Million People in Somalia, U.N. Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- More than a million people
are at risk of famine in central and southern Somalia, the United
Nations has issued the warning as it launched a joint appeal for
1.7 million U.S. dollars for the next six months to cover
emergency relief in the region, U.N. officials said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was launched Wednesday in Nairobi, capital of Kenya,
by the Somalia Aid Coordination Body, a group of U.N. agencies,
donor countries, and relief organizations. The U.N. estimates that
30,000 tons of food will be needed to feed a million people over
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
The lack of rain, poor harvest and a shortage of pasture and
water for livestock have affected cop yields, the U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Increased factional fighting, generally instability and higher
food import prices have also undermined food security for
vulnerable groups, they said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Food Security Assessment Unit says more than 30,000
tons of food are needed for an estimated 1 million people for
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
After a two-year absence due to dangerous conditions, the
U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF) sent two expatriate workers back
to Baidoa last month to beef up the local Somali staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
