<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Consider Scaling back Special Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The organizers have felt the
pressure from the increasing size of the Special Olympic World
Summer Games and are considering limiting the scale of future
games.
</P>
<P>
Special Olympics Inc., which organizes and guides the program
around the world, admitted that the games cannot grow much bigger
than it is now.
</P>
<P>
"There's only so much event organizers can do in hosting these
events. I think we saw it in Raleigh in these games. We were
starting to press the limit." said Lee Todd, vice president of
games and competition for Special Olympics Inc.
</P>
<P>
About 7,000 Special Olympians along with about 57,000
volunteers, coaches and relatives involved in the games that ended
Sunday in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
Todd revealed his concern that potential transportation
problems lie with shuttling athletes to and from ceremonies and
competitions.
</P>
<P>
He was also worried about the logistics of updating results and
schedules for the athletes.
</P>
<P>
Todd said that the 2003 Summer Games slated in Dublin will be
of the same size or smaller than this year with the number of
sports likely to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Special Olympics Inc. is also working on plans to organize
regional games and limit the scale of the World Games.
</P>
<P>
Todd said holding regional games in six locations around the
world would give the growing number of athletes a chance to
compete in high-profile competitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sets Out Fourfold Agenda For WTO Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Vice President of the European
Commission, Sir Leon Brittan, said here on Thursday that the
European Union (EU)'s executive branch has set out a fourfold
ambitious agenda for the Millennium Round of global trade talks to
be started this November in Seattle, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The agenda, among other things, includes further liberalization
and rule-making in the fields of agriculture and services,
non-agricultural tariffs, investment, competition, trade
facilitation, and trade and environment, Brittan said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He generalized the fourfold agenda point by point: first, to
secure further trade liberalization and market access, creating
conditions for competitiveness; second, to promote the further
strengthening of the World Trade Organization (WTO) system to that
it becomes a truly universal instrument for the management of
global trade; third, to take into account the continued need for
special and differential treatment for developing countries in
order to promote their development; and fourth, to ensure that the
WTO continues to address issues of concern to the broader public,
such as environment, health and social concerns.
</P>
<P>
"Our approach aims at cutting tariffs across the board, and
taking special account of the interests of the developing
countries. There can be no justification for developed countries
maintaining high tariff peaks in sectors such as textiles. This
has gone on too long and must be a major target in the New Round,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Comprehensive global trade talks offer opportunities which the
narrow sectoral approach never can. A new round offers benefits
not only to Europe, but to all members of the World Trade
Organization. Better trade rules and more market access are good
for business, good for growth, and good for jobs," the EU trade
chief added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
