<HEADLINE> India Recaptures Three Peaks in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Army has recaptured
two peaks in the Batalik sub-sector and one in the Drass sector of
Kashmir, killing 92 enemy soldiers while losing 38 of its own men,
Indian Army sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Troops of 11 Gorkha Rifles and a Bihar Regiment Battalion
recaptured the two peaks after night-long fierce fighting in the
Batalik sub-sector in operations to clear the peaks, they said.
</P>
<P>
With reinforcements entering some areas, Pakistani troops
launched counterattack at four positions but were effectively
repulsed, they said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 634 Pakistani regulars have reportedly been killed
in Kargil while India has lost 321 men including 23 officers since
the Indian operation began on May 8.
</P>
<P>
The sources said there was no qualitative change on the ground
in Kargil after Sunday's meeting between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. Islamabad
showed "no signs" of abiding by its commitment to pull back its
troops and extremist elements from the Indian side of the Line of
Control (LOC), they said.
</P>
<P>
An External Affairs Ministry spokesman said here, "We are
concentrating on our military operations... The operations are
going on and we are in the process of evicting the intruders."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the prospects of the Lahore peace process
being resumed once India drives out the infiltrators, he said New
Delhi has a larger vision of developing cooperative relations with
all the neighboring countries including Pakistan. India would
consider the question of bringing back on track the composite
dialogue process only after the Pakistan "misadventure" ended.
</P>
<P>
Sharif just returned to his country earlier Thursday from his
U.S.-Britain visits and was expected to convene several important
meetings in the coming couple of days to discuss his visits and
the situation along the Indo-Pakistani border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
