<HEADLINE> China, Japan Enter Final Stage of WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan have entered the
final stage of their talks on China's accession into the World
Trade Organization (WTO), sources said.
</P>
<P>
Inside sources gave Xinhua details after attending the talks
between Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) Shi Guangsheng, and Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura and Posts and Telecommunications Minister Seiko Noda, who
both arrived here Thursday afternoon with Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
"Following tense negotiations over the past few weeks between
the Japanese and Chinese delegations, we have entered the final
stage of talks on China's accession to the WTO," said the MOFTEC
official, who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached agreements in most fields, and both sides are
satisfied with the results," he said.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng expressed thanks to Japan for
its consistent support on China's WTO accession. He stressed that
China's bid to enter the multi-lateral trade body, which has
lasted for 13 years, is necessary because of China's current drive
in its reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts to enter the WTO are dictated and demanded by this
drive," he said. "China's entry in the WTO, on the other hand,
will help push forward the reform of the world trade system and
the development of world trade."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that whether China enters the WTO will not affect
China's determination to firmly carry on its reform and opening
policy.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks with the Japanese ministers, Shi told Toyota
Shoichiro, newly-elected president of the Japan-China Investment
Promotion Organization, and other Japanese entrepreneurs during a
separate meeting that Japanese entrepreneurs can play a more
active role in the development of bilateral trade and economic
cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
