<HEADLINE> Thai Supreme Commander Hails Army Relationship with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Almost all senior military leaders
in Thailand have visited China in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
The fourth Thai military magnate to arrive in Beijing is the
supreme commander of the Thai armed forces Mongkon Ampornpisit,
who follows in the footsteps of the Thai Prime Minister and
defense minister, the deputy defense minister and the commander of
the army.
</P>
<P>
Now that the Thai economy is back on an upswing, the Thai
military immediately resumed its frequent visits to China, as was
the rule before Thailand became mired in a financial crisis two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"This not only shows that Thailand attaches great importance to
military relations and other bilateral ties, but also testifies to
the fact that Thailand and China are 'inseparable'," Mongkon told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
"China is an influential country in the Asia-Pacific region,
with whom Thailand and other southeast Asian nations have the same
or similar views."
</P>
<P>
Mongkon noted that "Thailand and China share the same origins
in terms of politics, society and culture, as well as an identical
or similar stand toward many major international issues."
</P>
<P>
"We have no differences at all," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"I believe, that every Thai person will never forget that China
was the first country to extend a helping hand to our country" in
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
As the leader of the Thai army, Mongkon expressed his
satisfaction over the relations between the two armed forces: "The
two armies are carrying out efficient cooperation in various
fields," he said, adding that the exchange of visits and
servicemen training, as well as exchanges in the defense sector
have shown good momentum.
</P>
<P>
At this juncture, Mongkon pointed to a Chinese serviceman who
worked as an interpreter for him: "We are glad that he studied in
Thailand and was crowned as the best foreign student in a Thai
military academy."
</P>
<P>
When the Asian financial crisis broke out two years ago,
Mongkon came to China as a government envoy to discuss with the
Chinese side measures to overcome the crisis. Now he is endowed
with the task of further elevating army relationships.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian, Mongkon
remarked, "You visited Thailand five times, but I've been here six
times, I hope that you can beat my record some time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
