<HEADLINE> EU Commission Proposes Priorities for WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission put
forward on Thursday its proposals for the agenda of the Millennium
Round of global trade talks to be launched this November in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive arm said the final
proposals lay out both the case for a comprehensive round and
proposed EU priorities.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive round is the best mechanism for breaking down
the remaining barriers to trade, the Commission said in a
statement. "It will improve the European economy, foster economic
growth worldwide, and ensure the successful management of
globalization."
</P>
<P>
In the policy document, the EU executive body stresses the need
to achieve greater market access by reducing tariffs and non-
tariff barriers and improving market access in the services sector.
</P>
<P>
It also emphasizes the importance of developing new rules
governing trade and investment, trade and competition, and rules
aimed at facilitating trade.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations in all these areas should take full account of
the needs of developing countries and the objective of sustainable
development," the Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The European commission's policy proposals have been submitted
to the EU's 15 member states and the European Parliament for
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
