<HEADLINE> Canadian Sperm Bank Users Urged for Disease Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is urging
all the sperm bank users to be tested for a variety of
communicable diseases.
</P>
<P>
The move, announced Wednesday afternoon, came after the recent
official finding that 35 of the country's 49 sperm banks have
sloppy record-keeping and inconsistent testing.
</P>
<P>
In a letter delivered Wednesday, Health Canada official Robert
Peterson demands all Canadian fertility clinics inform their
consumers of the "small possibility" of infection.
</P>
<P>
"This is to advise you that as a precautionary measure, Health
Canada strongly recommends notification and testing of all
recipients of donor semen for infectious agents," writes the
health official.
</P>
<P>
The consequent diseases may include hepatitis B and hepatitis C,
HTLV-1/11, syphilis, chlamydia, neisseria, gonorrhea and CMV,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
In a Wednesday press release, however, the Canadian Health
Department said that it has not received any report of
transmission of infection through semen since federal regulations
were established in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 3,000 Canadian women are inseminated
each year through sperm banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
