<HEADLINE> Russia Against Discrimination in Balkan Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Thursday that
international economic aid should be provided "to all countries
hit by the Balkan conflict without any discrimination."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said
discrimination based on artificial politicization or division of
regimes should be avoided "lest new dividing barriers be built."
</P>
<P>
"From the outset of the Kosovo crisis Russia has been calling
for a comprehensive solution to the humanitarian problem of all
the residents of Yugoslavia whatever their religion or ethnicity,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The West has insisted that the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia be
barred from any major economic assistance as long as President
Slobodan Milosevic stays in power.
</P>
<P>
NATO's 78-day bombing campaign has crippled much of Yugoslavia
's infrastructure such as oil refineries, power-generating
facilities, roads and bridges. Automobile factories and tobacco
plants, government buildings and many residential buildings were
also destroyed or damaged in the air raids.
</P>
<P>
"A normal, functioning economy" is a major factor which can
ensure that human rights are observed, Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
Once the military phase of the Kosovo crisis is over, then
rebuilding the country's socioeconomic structure, destroyed by
NATO strikes, becomes the most urgent task, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Because there is no mutual understanding with its Western
partners on this issue, Russia wants the most obvious damage
repaired through humanitarian aid," the Interfax news agency
quoted Rakhmanin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia backs "the U.N. secretary-general's understanding of
humanitarian aid to Yugoslavia as including the rebuilding of
power and water supply systems, clearing the Danube, etc., rather
than only supplies of food stuffs and medicine which the Americans
and Britons insist upon," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
