<HEADLINE> IOM Starts Airlifting Kosovo Refugees Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The first group of Kosovo refugees who
had been given shelter in Germany were flown back home on Thursday
under the auspices of the International Organization for Migration
(IOM).
</P>
<P>
Some 160 ethnic Albanian refugees boarded a plane at Muenster-
Osnabrueck airport, in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia, to
Skopje, Macedonia, where they were to be bused home.
</P>
<P>
Germany hosted the biggest single contingent of 14,689 Kosovo
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Geneva-based IOM Thursday began to repatriate
Kosovar Albanians from other European countries, the United States,
Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Between April 5 and July 5, the IOM and the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) flew 91,057 refugees out of
overcrowded refugee camps in Macedonia. 
</P>
