<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ballot Registration Materials Arrive in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Forty cases containing ballot
registration materials arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, on
Thursday from Darwin, Australia, aboard a U.N. aircraft, the
Antara News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, head of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)'s
Ballot Section, and other UNAMET staff were present at the airport
to pick up the cases.
</P>
<P>
"The cases will be immediately distributed among UNAMET
representative offices in 13 district capitals in East Timor,
where they will be redistributed among 200 registration centers,"
said UNAMET spokesman Ueki Yasuhiro.
</P>
<P>
In the near future, several hundred more cases containing the
same materials will arrive in East Timor, he said.
</P>
<P>
If all registration facilities and infrastructures are ready
and preparations for the assignment of registration personnel have
been made, the registration scheduled for July 13 can run
smoothly, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 15 liaison officers have arrived in Dili,
including three from the United States, one from Australia, two
from Malaysia, two from Thailand, five from Brazil and two from
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold the direct ballot in August.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will allow the territory's people to choose whether
their homeland should become an autonomous region within Indonesia
or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
