<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drifting Bottles Set Adrift On Voyage to North Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, ARCTIC BOUND July 8 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese
scientist is following in the wake of the great ocean explorer
Columbus by casting a number of bottles with messages into the
ocean on his voyage to the North Pole as part of China's first
government sponsored Arctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
Meng Guanglin has thrown a sealed bottle into the sea every
latitude since the expedition ship, Snow Dragon, left Shanghai on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I prepared 50 bottles and the last one will be put on the ice
in the Arctic Ocean. There is the possibility that someone,
somewhere may find one of the bottles or even more, most probably
in the northern hemisphere," said Meng, from the State Oceanic
Environment Monitoring Center in Dalian City in northeastern China
's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The great Spanish voyager, Columbus, dropped a bottle into the
sea not long before he died in an accident in 1498. It was found
on a deserted beach 358 years later.
</P>
<P>
Residents and visitors in the Alaska State of the United States,
Russia's Siberia and the coastal areas of Europe are the most
likely to encounter Meng's bottles. "But all the coastal areas in
the northern hemisphere cannot be ruled out," said Meng, who has
been interested in the sea since he was a child.
</P>
<P>
The plastic bottles, previously used to hold mineral water,
were sealed with glue and inside each carries a number, and the
time and place when it was sent off on its journey into the
unknown.
</P>
<P>
An envelope, carrying the words "The First Chinese National
Arctic Research Expedition and Research Vessel Xuelong's Maiden
Voyage to Arctic" both in Chinese and English, and including Meng'
s address is also sealed in each of the bottles.
</P>
<P>
Meng hopes someone will contact him even after one or two
decades. But maybe he will never receive any answer to his letters.
"The ocean is not a reliable postman," he joked.
</P>
<P>
"If we are so fortunate that someone encounters the bottles in
the future, they will be of great research and collection value,"
said Meng, adding that it will help scientists research the
movement of ocean currents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
