<HEADLINE> Cambodian Human Rights Workers Tried for Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Cambodian rights workers
were tried Thursday in the southwestern city of Sihanoukville on
charges of inciting violence during last December's protests
against the dumping of toxic waste in Cambodia by a Taiwan
company.
</P>
<P>
Meas Minear, 30, and Kim Sen, 37, were charged with involvement
in illegal demonstrations and incitement leading to violence and
property damage.
</P>
<P>
The two staff members of the Cambodian League for Promotion and
Defense for Human Rights were arrested after two days of protests
last December and had been detained for a month.
</P>
<P>
The dumping of nearly 3,000 tones of toxic wastes, shipped from
Taiwan on November 30 by a Taiwan company, prompted violent
protests and caused panic among the residents in Sihanoukville.
</P>
<P>
Protesters, enraged by the danger of the wastes, destroyed the
building of the goods-inspection office and looted the villa of
the city's deputy governor.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least four died and 18 were injured in
the protests and road accidents as residents fled the town.
</P>
<P>
According to court officials the trial would continue on
Friday. 
</P>
