<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Adopts Extra Job Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government Thursday
approved a 519.8 billion yen (4.3 billion U.S. dollar)
supplementary budget for fiscal 1999 to finance a set of measures
to improve the country's deteriorating employment situation.
</P>
<P>
The extra budget, approved in a cabinet meeting, was
immediately sent to the Diet (parliament). It is expected to be
enacted on July 19 at the earliest, with debate starting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government aims to create more than 700,000 new
jobs by adopting the extra budget, the first for the current
fiscal year which began on April 1.
</P>
<P>
The extra budget allocates the 519.8 billion yen to a general
account. Along with 23.1 billion yen (about 189 million dollars)
in new spending allotted to special accounts such as one covering
employment insurance, the amount of fresh government spending for
jobs totals 542.9 billion yen (4.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The general-account portion of the auxiliary budget features
204.7 billion yen (1.7 billion dollars) in spending for the
central and local governments to hire about 300,000 more workers
on a temporary basis within two years.
</P>
<P>
Other major pillars of the supplementary budget are 200.3
billion yen (1.6 billion dollars) in spending to tackle the low
birthrate, and 90 billion yen (738 million dollars) to create 150,
000 new jobs in 15 promising industries including the medical and
welfare sector, telecommunications industries and environment-
related businesses.
</P>
<P>
Japan's unemployment rate stood at a record 4.8 percent in
March and April. It was slightly improved to 4.6 percent in May.
However, many Japanese private economists expect the figure to
rise above 5 percent toward the year-end as companies engaged in
restructuring are shedding workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
