<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges Middle Course in Ties With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
Thursday that Moscow would follow a middle-of-the-road course when
dealing with the West, avoiding both direct confrontation and
unquestioning friendship.
</P>
<P>
In an address to military leaders in the Kremlin, Yeltsin said
Russia's relations with NATO and the United States "remain
delicate and difficult."
</P>
<P>
"We will not confront NATO directly, but we will not flirt
with them either," Yeltsin said, "We shall closely follow NATO's
moves and work out our tactics together."
</P>
<P>
Russia's ties with NATO, already strained because of the
military alliance's eastward expansion, plummeted to a new low
when NATO staged a 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Only limited contacts have been resumed between NATO and
Moscow in areas concerning the peacekeeping operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also singled out Russia's envoy to NATO, Col. Gen.
Viktor Zavarzin, to praise him for leading about 200 paratroopers
into Pristina on June 12, ahead of NATO troops' arrival.
</P>
<P>
"Russian servicemen must be presented with medals for Kosovo,"
Yeltsin said. Russian media reported that Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin would go to the Yugoslav province later this month to
present awards to the paratroopers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
