<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens High-Level Scientific Cooperation With Western Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China and the European Union (EU)
are to start joint high-tech research programs this year which
marks a new phase of Sino-EU scientific cooperation, according to
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Xu revealed today in an interview with Xinhua that China and
the EU will, for the first time, make available to each other on a
reciprocal basis high-tech research and development programs based
on a Sino-EU draft agreement involving such cooperation signed
some months ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU has agreed to open its 17 billion US dollar
1998 to 2002 scientific research program, the fifth in a series,
to allow Chinese scientists to take part in research programs
covering the fields of biology, energy, aviation, space,
telecommunications and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister added, "China will also push for further high-
level cooperation with other world giants in terms of scientific
advancement."
</P>
<P>
Concerning cooperation with the U.S., Xu explained that China
is to promote more joint R&AMP;D programs, focused on pharmaceuticals,
telecommunications, new materials, micro electronics, agriculture
and will seek cooperation in basic research fields such as high-
energy physics, space, human genetics and other major scientific
research fields.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance of high-level scientific
cooperation with Russia in aviation, space, nuclear energy, space
station and a number of other fields.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shaoqi, director of the international cooperation
department of the Ministry of Science and Technology, said his
ministry and the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and National
Natural Science Foundation have jointly decided to invest 12
million yuan (1.4 million US dollars) for building several high-
energy physical installations for the European Center for Nuclear
Research.
</P>
<P>
He said this would enable more Chinese scientists to attend
research programs there. So far nearly 100 Chinese scientists are
working in the center.
</P>
<P>
The CAS, China's top scientific research body, has already
decided to allocate funds to several major Sino-foreign joint
research programs and some of its branches in other parts of China
will establish partner labs with EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the new trend in Sino-foreign scientific
cooperation, Wang said the raising of cooperation levels in this
field has encouraged cooperation in the respective industrial
sectors as well as promoting foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1997 there were a total of 8,
352 EU funded projects with over 30 billion US dollars of actual
contracted investment registered in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
