<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Exchanges, Clearing Houses to Be Merged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A new holding company, known as
the Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing Limited (HKEC), will be set
up as a result of the planned demutualization and merger of Hong
Kong's stock exchange, futures exchange and clearing houses.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
Thursday published a paper setting out the business model and the
public policy framework for the new company.
</P>
<P>
The merger is in pursuance of the market structure reform
announced by the financial secretary in March, under which the two
exchanges and the three associated clearing houses in Hong Kong
will be merged by March 2000.
</P>
<P>
HKEC will be a public listed company owned by private investors
and the government, but the government's role would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
The board of the company will comprise directors elected by
shareholders and those representing public and market interests.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the market reform is to enhance the market's
competitiveness so as to meet the challenge of an increasingly
globalized market place driven by advancement of technology and
the emergence of a growing population of sophisticated investors,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The merger is expected to increase transparency and efficiency,
open up the field to more players and ultimately attract more
companies to list in Hong Kong, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Acting Financial Secretary of the SAR, Rafael Hui, announced
Thursday that Financial Secretary Donald Tsang has appointed
Charles Lee as chairman of the preparatory board of HKEC and
Dannis Lee and John Strickland as its directors.
</P>
<P>
Hui is appointed a director of the preparatory board of HKEC as
the representative of the government's interest.
</P>
<P>
Charles Lee is a member of the Executive Council of the SAR and
was former chairman of the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Dannis Lee is currently chairman of the Hong Kong Stockbrokers
Association and Strickland is the former chairman of the Hong Kong
and Shanghai Banking Corporation Limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
