<HEADLINE> U.N. Employee Accused of Sabotage Leaves Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations employee accused
by Iraq of carrying out acts of sabotage in northern Iraq left
Baghdad on Thursday morning, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said Ayan Broughton, known as Red, a New Zealander, left
Baghdad on Thursday morning and is on his way to Amman, Jordan
after it was proved that he carried out sabotage acts aimed at
harming Iraq's agriculture resources.
</P>
<P>
An official with the U.N. Office of Humanitarian Coordinator
in Iraq (UNOHCI) confirmed that Broughton had left Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Broughton, a supervisor at the U.N. Office of Project Services
entrusted with removing land mines in northern Iraq's Suleimaniya
province, was accused by Iraq of attempting to spread agriculture
pests in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said Broughton entered Kalar subdistrict in Suleimaniya in
April this year, and buried several boxes of suspicious material
nearby.
</P>
<P>
Residents in that area later dug out those boxes and found that
the boxes were containing eggs of locusts.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government condemned the act and demanded that
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan investigate it to reveal all the
parties involved. Iraq also demands that Broughton be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Foreign Ministry summoned U.N. Coordinator in Iraq
Hans Von Sponeck earlier in the week and handed him a memorandum
of protest calling for ordering Broughton out of Iraq within 72
hours.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly accused United States and British
nationals working in northern Iraq, particularly those working
with non-governmental organizations, of spying on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Iraq asked the U.N. to replace U.S. and
British nationals working with U.N. agencies in central and
southern Iraq with staff of other nationalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
