<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Unveils Plans for Football Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Italians will be well entertained by
soccer feast next season after the football League unveiled plans
for seven-days-a-week T.V. coverage.
</P>
<P>
The Serie A, which was traditionally played on Sundays, will be
split every weekend between Saturday and Sunday with Serie B
matches broadcast on Mondays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
Tuesdays and Wednesdays will see the enlarged Champions League
matches and the re-vamped UEFA Cup on Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
Saturday has at least two Serie A matches and the kick-off time
on Sunday will be fixed at 3.00pm, ending the seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
Spare slots during the week, when European action takes a rest
between rounds, will meanwhile be filled up with Italian Cup ties.
</P>
<P>
League boss Franco Carraro said that the fixed Sunday kick-off
time would be "something which will be good for football and for
family life".
</P>
<P>
"With the different kick-off times, it's always been difficult
for families to organise Sundays so that everybody is happy," said
Carraro.
</P>
<P>
Aside from improving the family life, the changes are
principally designed to exploit the rapidly emerging market for
subscription and pay-per-view television here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
