<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Marigold Has Bright Prospect Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Overseas demand for Thailand-grown
marigolds is steadily increasing as the flowers are not only
well-known for their natural beauty, but also for useful
substances embedded, the Thai News Agency (TNA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Marigold or Tagetes Erecta contains nutrient substances that
are useful for animals and can be used to produce animal feed,
including those for pets and poultry, the TNA quoted a botanical
expert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sermsin Klinchantr, president of the Thai Marigold Producers'
Society, said the nutrient substances are particularly in the
strain of red-yellow marigold while the yellow-strain flowers are
widely used for decorations and making garlands.
</P>
<P>
Demand for Thailand-grown red-yellow marigolds as raw materials
for animal feed has been steadily increasing in overseas markets,
especially in the United States, she said.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the growing importance of the strain, the Thai
Marigold Producers' Society has launched a pilot project to
promote mass production of red-yellow marigolds to meet the
increasing demand, both locally and abroad, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The project is being implemented by member groups in different
regions, with a targeted production of 13,000 tons countrywide
this year on an overall area of 20,000 rai (3,200 hectares), she
said.
</P>
<P>
Sermsin said demand for marigolds in the United States is an
average of between 30,000 and 50,000 tons a year, while the
production capacity of the red-yellow-strain flower in Thailand is
about 50,000 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The figure shows that if the pilot project to boost the
production of Thai marigolds becomes successful, massive
value-added earnings can be created for local growers in the
foreseeable future, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
