<HEADLINE> UNITA-Downed Plane Not Military: Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Angolan government has firmly denied
UNITA's saying that the plane downed last Thursday in the
northeast of the country had on board senior officers of the
government army.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Angola Daily quoted a statement from the Information
Ministry as saying that the Antonov-12 plane belonged to a private
transport company Savanair.
</P>
<P>
An indenture provided by the company showed that the plane was
loaded with 12 tons of civil goods, including flour, maize flour,
sausage and beer.
</P>
<P>
Besides the five Russian crew members on board, there are only
two Angolans escorting the goods.
</P>
<P>
"After downing two U.N. airplanes in a row, the armed forces of
(Jonas) Savimbi once again cruelly attacked civil airplanes. It
could only demonstrate the terrorist, inhumane and belligerent
elements," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on public opinion, at home and abroad, to
condemn such act by the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) to prevent more civil planes from being targeted
and downed.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government issued a statement Tuesday, demanding
the release of arrested Russian pilots. It also denied that they
were offering assistance to the Angolan government army.
</P>
<P>
On May 12, another Antonov-26 plane was downed in the same
area. The three Russian pilots were arrested.
</P>
<P>
UNITA had accused the Russian pilots of being mercenaries, and
asked for their due trial and punishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
