<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- A ceasefire agreement in the Democratic Republic of Congo
was signed on Wednesday in Lusaka, Zambia, after 13 days of
negotiations by the foreign ministers and defense ministers of all
the countries involved in the conflict, as well as representatives
of the rebel groups. The heads of state of the countries involved
will meet in a summit in Lusaka to formally adopt the truce
agreement to put an end to a one-year continental scale conflict
which devastated former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
-- Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and Foday Sankoh, respectively the chief
of government and chief of rebels of Sierra Leone, signed a peace
agreement on Wednesday to end a bloody conflict which has ruined
the small and once prosperous western African state. The
agreement led to a power sharing between the former government and
the rebels, who have obtained four minister's portfolios, and the
commission in charge of the country's mineral wealth.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French authority of sales guardianship, the Committee of
Establishment of Credit, Wednesday approved a plan by the Banque
Nationale de Paris (BNP) to buy more than 50.01 percent of the
capitals of two other French private banks, the Paribas and
Societe Generale (SG). Therefore, the merger battle between BNP
as one side, and Paribas and SG as the other is expected to end
this month.
</P>
<P>
-- The Pentagon has expressed its support to acquisition by
Europeans of American arms industries. Jack Gansler, under-
secretary of the U.S. Defense Department, said on Wednesday that
he expected many mergers to take place between European and
American armaments manufacturing groups in the coming months.
</P>
</TEXT>
