<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Dismisses Iraqi Accusation of Sabotage by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Office of
Humanitarian Coordinator in Iraq (UNOHCI) on Thursday dismissed
the Iraqi accusation that a U.N. employee carried out acts of
sabotage in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
UNOHCI said in a statement that "neither Ayan Broughton, nor
any other U.N.-related person was in the area identified by the
Iraqi authorities on April 8."
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused Broughton, known as Red, a New Zealander working
as a supervisor at the U.N. Office of Project Services which is
entrusted with removing land mines in northern Iraq's Suleimaniya
province, of attempting to spread agriculture pests on April 8.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said Broughton entered Kalar subdistrict in Suleimaniya
and buried several boxes of suspicious material nearby. Residents
in that area later dug out those boxes and found that they were
containing eggs of locusts.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the Iraqi government, in a verbal note
to U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator in Iraq Hans von Sponeck on
Tuesday, requested that Broughton leave the country within 72
hours.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported that Broughton left
Baghdad on Thursday morning. An official with UNOHCI who asked not
to be identified confirmed that Broughton had left Baghdad for
Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, UNOHCI said that "the investigation carried
out by the U.N., including evidence from witnesses... seems to
suggest a case of mistaken identity."
</P>
<P>
The statement did not explain why Broughton left Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has demanded that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
investigate the incident, said INA.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has repeatedly accused United States and British
nationals working in Iraq's three northern Kurdish autonomous
provinces, particularly those working with non-governmental
organizations, of spying on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Iraq asked the U.N. to replace U.S. and
British nationals working with U.N. agencies in central and
southern Iraq with staff of other nationalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fastest Train Undergoing Trials (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's fastest passenger train
started its first tests this morning at the China Academy of
Railway Science's Loop Line Test Center in Beijing's eastern
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
It is capable of speeds of up to 200 kilometers per hour and is
a key step towards express railway transportation, according to
Liu Youmei, an electric engine specialist, who explained that the
train will have further tests at 200 km per hour in the Guangzhou-
Shenzhen line, where it will be used later.
</P>
<P>
One imported train and several trains made in China, whose
highest speed is 160 km per hour, are currently being used on the
line.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the new train has an engine, a driver car at the
end, and five coaches produced by different locomotive or coach
factories in six different provinces.
</P>
<P>
China's first electric engine was made in 1958. In 1996, the
country succeeded in making the first semi-high-speed engine,
which hit a record test speed of 240 km per hour in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhonghao, the deputy director of the Railway Ministry's
Department of Science, Technology and Education, said that the 200-
km-per-hour train has an important role in China's high-speed
railway development. China expects to build a series of passenger
lines like the Qinghuangdao-Shenyang Route, which is under
construction, to increase market demand for such trains, Li added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fastest Train Undergoing Trials (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has about 70,000 km. of railway lines and an annual
passenger volume of 900 million people. But, in spite of
improvements in 1997 and 1998, the fastest passenger train still
doesn't do more than 160 km per hour, which doesn't meet the needs
for greater efficiency.
</P>
<P>
So, China is planning to start work on its first high-speed
railway, the Beijing-Shanghai express line, connecting China's
capital and its biggest industrial city with a train that can
travel 300 km per hour. At the same time, research departments are
actively trying to improve the technology for these trains.
</P>
<P>
Rong Chaohe, a professor of transport economics at Northern
China Jiaotong University, said that although there has been rapid
progress in aviation and expressways in the past decade, over-
populated countries, which are threatened by worsening
environmental conditions, will finally choose high-speed railways
as a major means of transportation for their obvious advantages:
ability, less land use, energy saving, and safety.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that China's railway transportation
volume accounts for 85 percent of the country's total long-and-
medium distance transportation volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Approves Record Number of China Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved a record 19
projects in China during the fiscal year of 1999 (FY99) which
ended June 30, with an investment totaling 2,097 million U.S.
dollars, according to sources from the WB's Resident Mission in
China.
</P>
<P>
The new commitments include 1,674.4 million U.S. dollars within
the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD)
loan scheme and 422.6 million U.S. dollars in credits from the
International Development Association (IDA).
</P>
<P>
Since 1982, the WB's total cumulative lending to China has
amounted to some 32.45 billion U.S. dollars, of which about 22.25
billion U.S. dollars from the IBRD and about 10.20 billion U.S.
dollars from the IDA, financing a total of 218 projects.
</P>
<P>
The FY99 is the last in which China can benefit from the
concessional IDA credits, according to WB sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the WB's assistance program is now targeted at
the poorer and institutional weaker inland provinces, and the
amount of lending per project has been scaled back to suit the
actual financial needs of those provinces, leading to a lowering
of the lending level as compared with the 2,616.4 million U.S.
dollars in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
About half of the 19 projects approved in FY99 have directly
supported poverty alleviation and social objectives, while the
others have supported infrastructure development also mostly in
the interior parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of the WB's lending program in China mirrors the
government's efforts to cope with the Asian financial crisis,"
says Yukon Huang, Director of the World Bank China Program. "
Several of our projects in FY99 have supported the critical reform
initiatives of the government, such as those in the accounting and
pensions systems, state-owned enterprises and container transport.
"
</P>
<P>
"Other projects were designed to ensure that the benefits of
China's rapid growth reach the poor in the central and western
regions. Particularly noteworthy, in the wake of last year's
devastating floods along the Yangtze River, was the speed with
which the Government and the World Bank prepared a Flood Emergency
Rehabilitation Project to assist in the reconstruction of basic
infrastructure in three affected provinces," he added.
</P>
<P>
In FY99, the WB has also produced a number of analytical
studies and reports focused on the issues and challenges facing
China in its development and transition to a socialist market
economy, including the latest country economic report China:
Weathering the Storm and Learning the lessons, which elaborates on
China's success in avoiding the effects of the Asian financial
crisis and policy options for the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Karachi stocks Thursday closed
marginally lower with the 100-share price index fell 4.35 points,
or 0.39 points, to 1,105.67 points from Wednesday's 1,110.2.
</P>
<P>
The volume on Thursday stood at 163.146 million shares against
Wednesday's 193.638 million.
</P>
<P>
Of the 150 active issues, 59 registered gains, 38 sustained
losses and 53 remained unchanged. 
</P>
