<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Tour Cyclist Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Tour de France saw the first
cyclist testing positive for corticosteroids after the race's
prologue, sports daily L'Equipe reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Corticosteroids, anti-inflammatory and painkilling drugs which
are not classed as steroids, are banned unless prescribed by
doctors for specific medical conditions such as asthma and
rhinitis.
</P>
<P>
Four cyclists were tested after Saturday's prologue, including
the winner of the stage Lance Armstrong of the United States.
Denmark's Bo Hamburger, Manuel Beltran of Spain and Colombian
Joaquim Castelblanco were the others tested. But L'Equipe didn't
say who tested posidive.
</P>
<P>
Jacques de Ceaurriz, the official who carried out the test,
refused to confirm or deny the report, saying it is up to the
International Cycling Union to act on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Ceaurriz's laboratory has recently developed what it claims is
a foolproof method of detecting corticosteroids in urine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
