<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Fund For Protecting Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A special Sino-Japanese fund has
been set up as part of the growing campaign to protect the
endangered giant pandas in China.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "Friends of Giant Pandas" it is a joint project by
the China Wildlife Conservation Association and Japan's Future
Generation Alliance Foundation (FGAF), with the Japanese side
contributing 2.1 million yuan (253,000 US dollars) to the fund in
the initial stage.
</P>
<P>
Katsuhiko Yazaki, chairman of FGAF, promised that it will
contribute a further 10 million Japanese yen (82,600 US dollars)
to the fund every year from now on.
</P>
<P>
Ma Fu, deputy director of China's State Forestry Administration,
said that it is always a long and arduous task to protect
endangered animals such as giant pandas. "We hope that this
cooperative scheme will further arouse public awareness to help
save this wonderful species of animals."
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas once thrived in China and roamed widely during the
Pleistocene Epoch but can now only be found in high mountains and
deep valleys in parts of China's Sichuan, Shaanxi and Gansu
provinces due to natural changes and human encroachment.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are only about 1,000 giant pandas
surviving in the wild. Feeding mainly on arrow bamboo, they are
graceful, gentle and good-natured.
</P>
<P>
China has always attached great importance to the protection of
giant pandas and in 1992, the country launched a special project
to protect them as well as their habitats.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, 25 nature reserves, totaling over 1,000 square
kilometers, have been established in regions where giant pandas
live, and 95 percent of them are well protected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tides Fade Away in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The red tides in north China's
Bohai Sea that were reported earlier by the State Oceanic
Administration have disappeared due to climatic changes.
</P>
<P>
A monitoring vessel sent by the administration has detected
that the red tides were retreating in sea areas close to Cangzhou
City, Hebei Province, and the old river-mouth of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The administration reported Monday that the red tides were
found spreading rapidly in the sea areas, covering 1,500 square
kilometers close to Cangzhou and 400 square kilometers at the old
river-mouth.
</P>
<P>
The administration attributed the fading away of the red tides
to successive winds, rainfalls and low temperatures in the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
People living in coastal areas have been urged to pay greater
attention to red tides and report them to the authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRC Peace Summit Slated for Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The long-expected regional summit to
endorse a ceasefire agreement by all the warring parties involved
in the 11-month war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) will
be held here Saturday, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Copies of the documents in English, French and Portuguese to be
signed at the summit are being sent to the heads of state or
government of the countries concerned, said Chiluba, who has been
mandated by the Southern African Development Community (SADC) to
mediate a peaceful solution to the conflict in the third largest
African country.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state or government will be fully aware of the
ceasefire agreement and the modalities to implement it before they
come to Lusaka for the summit because each of them has a copy of
the documents, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was very proud to say it is a African paper in which
all contentious issues have been trashed out.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka document, hammered out in 13 days of tough talks in
the Zambian capital, says the United Nations Security Council, in
collaboration with the Organization of African Unity, will be
asked to create and deploy a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for national dialog between congolese political
groups, creation of a new national army, release of prisoners of
war and humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba commended the ministers and rebels upon their
negotiations on and adoption of the draft ceasefire agreement,
saying the agreement is the product of serious negotiations
involving the government of DRC and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He called for international material and financial support for
DRC to enable the peace process to succeed.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president also called on all parties involved to
stick to the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
After negotiations, ministers and representatives of 18 African
 countries including all the warring nations and rebels finalized
the draft ceasefire agreement and adopted it unanimously here
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Cooperation Needed for Financial Reform: Yam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Joseph Yam, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), Thursday called on
regional and international cooperation for reforming the existing
international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks at the third HKMA Distinguished Lecture,
Yam said that the existing international financial architecture
has failed to keep pace with the globalization of financial
markets and with technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
"The crises over the past two years have taught us that, no
matter how well maintained the domestic financial environment may
be, serious problems persist in what has proved to be an
increasingly volatile international financial system," Yam said.
</P>
<P>
These problems cannot be solved by individual economies on
their own, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the subject "Risks and Challenges of the
International Financial Scene," Jean-Claude Trichet, governor of
the Banque de France, offered his perspective on the reform of the
international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
He identified five key measures for strengthening the financial
systems of emerging economies against external shocks.
</P>
<P>
These include the adoption of the Basle Core Principles for
Effective Banking Supervision; deposit insurance schemes; policies
to encourage foreign direct investment; adoption of "liquidity-at-
risk" policy; and policies to discourage excessive short-term
foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
On the promotion of efficient functioning of global markets,
Trichet said that full and reliable transparency for all,
including both public and private sector entities, would be the
most effective measure for countering dangers arising from the "
herd instinct" of market participants.
</P>
<P>
Trichet emphasized the importance of designing and implementing
internationally agreed standards for ensuring effective
transparency at the international level and urged that ways should
be found to involve the private sector more effectively in crisis
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Donald Brash, governor of the Reserve Bank of New Zealand,
echoed Trichet's views on reforming the international financial
architecture.
</P>
<P>
He also considered that the most productive focus for
international and national economic reforms lay in the four key
areas of strengthening financial markets, reducing vulnerability
to short term capital flows, promoting greater transparency at all
levels, and involving private creditors in debt resolution
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA Distinguished Lecture was first launched in December
1996. The aim of the HKMA Distinguished Lecture is to provide a
forum for the local financial community to hear and exchange views
with influential figures from the international financial
community. Thursday's event was attended by over 500 participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Rightist Group Protests Against Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Activists of the Indian rightist
organization Shiv Sena pelted the Pakistan International Airlines
(PIA) office here with stones Thursday in protest against the
"manhandling of Indian High Commission officials" in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen of Shiv Sena activists converged behind the PIA
office in Connaught Place, a business center in the city, Thursday
afternoon and started pelting stones and shouted slogans against
Pakistan and its Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. The activists fled
the spot within minutes when they heard that PIA officials had
informed the police of the protest activities.
</P>
<P>
According to recent reports, a staff member of the Indian High
Commission in Islamabad and a Pakistani diplomat here have been
manhandled by "intelligence people" and both were expelled for
conducting "spying" activities.
</P>
<P>
Delhi Shiv Sena Chief Jai Bhagwan Goyal Thursday demanded
immediate closure of all Pakistani business establishments in the
country. "They cannot make money here and beat up our people there
and support anti-Indian forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the same organization burned the Pakistani flag
outside the Pakistani High Commission here, protesting against
what it called Pakistani intrusions in the Kargil sector of
Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
