<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Lowers Arab Expectations on Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel sought to lower Arab
expectations Thursday prior to Prime Minister Ehud Barak's first
peace initiative, saying his planned meetings with Arab leaders
are mainly designed to build trust.
</P>
<P>
Three days after his swearing-in, Barak will travel to
Alexandria Friday to meet Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
kicking off a series of meetings with peace partners including
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, Jordanian
King Abdullah and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"These meetings are first of all to break the ice, to create
an atmosphere of talk and mutual trust," Foreign Minister David
Levy told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The meetings are also designed to lower expectations, Levy added.
</P>
<P>
Arab leaders have welcomed the election of Barak, who ousted
hard-line Benjamin Netanyahu on a platform to revive the stalled
peace process on all tracks.
</P>
<P>
While presenting his coalition for approval Tuesday night,
Barak told the parliament that he will push forward the talks
with the Palestinians and Syria simultaneously, calling on Arab
leaders to join him in creating "peace of the brave."
</P>
<P>
Minister Without Portfolio Haim Ramon suggested Wednesday that
Barak might suggest to Mubarak, as well as Arafat and Clinton,
that Israel and the Palestinians bypass or partially implement
the Wye agreement, which was signed and then frozen by Netanyahu
last year.
</P>
<P>
Reports have said that Barak prefers the two sides to move
directly into final-status talks, but will seek Palestinian and
U.S. consent first.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have demanded that Israel first carry out the
Wye agreement in full.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to agree with our negotiating partners on a code
of behavior so that even if there will be problems, there won't
be a stalemate," Levy told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Syria promised Wednesday that it will reciprocate any peace
steps made by Barak. Levy welcomed the promise, but said Israel
wants to see concrete deeds so that there will be
confidence-building steps.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks broke off in early 1996. Damascus
has demanded that the talks be resumed on an Israeli
commitment to a full withdrawal from the Golan Heights,
seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan Keen to Promote Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, in
talks today with Kazakh Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Kasymzhomart Tokayev, said that China places great importance on
its relations with Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Tang and Tokayev expressed satisfaction with
the smooth development of bilateral ties. They agreed that the two
countries should increase mutually beneficial cooperation in all
areas, according to a Chinese foreign ministry official who
attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted the increased mutual understanding and trust between
the two countries since the establishment of diplomatic ties more
than seven years ago, saying that the two sides have maintained
close relations, and their cooperation has also seen new results.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the fact that Kazakhstan gives priority to
its relations with China in its diplomacy, the Chinese foreign
minister said, and China is fully prepared to promote its good-
neighborly ties and mutually beneficial cooperation with
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said that bilateral ties have developed in a stable
manner in recent years, and the two countries have successfully
settled border issues, and pointed out that the leaders of the two
countries have maintained frequent exchanges of visits, which is
significant to the growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kazakhstan will continue to further its good-
neighborly ties with China.
</P>
<P>
Tang and Tokayev also discussed bilateral economic and trade
ties and regional and international issues of common concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
