<HEADLINE> China Never Seeks Hegemony in Asia-Pacific: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China will not seek spheres of
influence, nor hegemonic power in the Asia-Pacific region, an
official from the Chinese Foreign Ministry said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yanyi, a Chinese Foreign Ministry official in charge of
China-ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) relations and
policy planning, made a speech on China's Asia-Pacific security
policies at the Center for International Studies of Thai Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A strong, stable and prosperous China is a factor in
establishing peace and prosperity of the Asia-Pacific region,
Yang said, adding that the relations between China and the rest of
the region will be further strengthened as China's economy
develops.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who is also in charge of multilateral security dialogue
and cooperation, proposed that Asia-Pacific countries enhance
mutual understanding and trust.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the South China Sea, she said that China has
already entered into broad guiding principles with ASEAN in their
1997 Joint Statement regarding the maintenance of regional peace
and stability and the settlement of disputes between countries
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Yang's visit to Thailand is part of the Sino-Thai official
exchange program, which was included in the relationship action
plan signed by the two countries' foreign ministers in Bangkok in
February this year. 
</P>
