<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Buddhist Statues On Display In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Eighty stone statues of Buddha that
remained hidden for more than 1,000 years in China's Shandong
Province will go on display tomorrow at the Museum of Chinese
History in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The statues were discovered at the site of Longxing Temple in
Shandong's Qingzhou County. They range in dates from the Northern
Wei Dynasty (386-534) to the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127),
according to archaeologists at the museum.
</P>
<P>
Qingzhou was a political and cultural center in eastern China
and had an important role in disseminating Buddhism in China. A
number of Buddhist statues discovered in the county were smuggled
abroad in 1994 and caught the attention of academics.
</P>
<P>
The more than 400 stone statues discovered at Longxing Temple
was one of China's 10 most important archaeological discoveries in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say that the Buddhist figures contain important
information about the spread of Buddhism in China, but they still
have not found out why the statues and Longxing Temple were
destroyed or who buried the broken statues.
</P>
<P>
It took archaeologists two years to restore the statues. And
the show will run till November 9. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
