<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Quenching War-fire, Major Task of OAU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing century is often
described as " a century of Africa's liberty and independence".
However, decades after decolonization and independence, peace and
stability remain the biggest challenges facing the continent.
</P>
<P>
Armed conflicts, either civil, bilateral or multilateral, are
still plaguing the continent 36 years after the founding of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), a continental organization
aimed at safeguarding independence, territorial integrity and
promoting cooperation in the continent.
</P>
<P>
About one third of the 53-member continental bloc are involved
in military conflicts directly or indirectly, all of them
suffering from the scourge of war and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
A military conflict erupted in early August last year in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and quickly spilt into a
regional one, sucking in as many as six other countries nearby.
Despite repeated meditations and peace talks by the OAU and other
regional and state leaders, the final peace is still not in sight.
</P>
<P>
It is encouraging, however, to see that most of the OAU members
are trying hard to bring the players of the 11-month-long conflict
to the negotiating table, and more encouraging to witness that
many of those involved in the armed conflicts in the Africa's
third biggest country, seem ready for peace. Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni signed a memorandum on peace with his DRC
counterpart Laurent Kabila on April 18 after talks in the Libyan
town of Sirte.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, under mounting economic
and social pressure at home, said in mid-June that he expected the
war to be over before the end of the year. "I think all of us have
learnt our lesson in the Congo," he told reporters in Pretoria,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Angola, another key player in the DRC conflict, also indicated
its reluctance to a prolonged war in DRC, as it has to "mend its
house".
</P>
<P>
After long talks and bargaining, ministers of countries
involved in the conflict made last-ditch efforts to narrow down
their differences and agreed on the modalities of a ceasefire pact
on July 7 in Lusaka, Zambia, paving the way for the regional
summit which was postponed several times.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere on the continent, peace is also twisted with Ethiopia
and Eritrea, two neighboring countries in the "Horn of Africa"
deadlocked in a border war.
</P>
<P>
Though both sides have repeatedly claimed that they respect the
11-point framework by the Addis Ababa-based OAU for an immediate
cease-fire and cessation of hostilities, fighting is still off and
on at the border.
</P>
<P>
Angola, which has been suffering over 20 years of civil war, is
still locked in military see-saws.
</P>
<P>
In Somali, Sierra Leone, Comoros and many other parts of the
continent, peace and stability are still nothing more than a dream
for many.
</P>
<P>
Since its birth, the 53-member OAU, which has set its eyes on,
among others, the promotion of unity and solidarity, the defending
of African countries' sovereignty, territorial integrity and
independence, still finds it difficult to promote and preserve
peace and stability in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Actually, OAU has, throughout the decades, set the resolving of
 conflicts in the continent as one of the top enshrined tasks.
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim proposed to establish,
within the organization, a mechanism for conflict prevention,
management and resolution, at the 1993 Cairo summit.
</P>
<P>
Now at the eve of the new millennium, OAU is trying to map out
a blueprint that can help make the organization more influential
and Africa more peaceful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
