<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki to Sign Congo Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki will join other regional heads of state in Zambia on
Saturday for the signing of a cease-fire deal on the war in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), a presidential aide said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki would travel to Lusaka on Saturday, spokesman Ronnie
Mamoepa said.
</P>
<P>
He would return home before traveling to Algiers to attend the
Organization of African Unity's (OAU) annual summit.
</P>
<P>
After lengthy talks, a draft cease-fire deal to end the
11-month war in the DRC was reached Wednesday in Lusaka by foreign
and defense ministers from countries involved in the conflict and
DRC rebel representatives.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the agreement, all hostilities should be ended
within 24 hours of the signing of the agreement, all armed groups
in the DRC should be disarmed, and the United Nations (UN)
security council, together with the OAU, should deploy a
peacekeeping force in the country to ensure the implementation of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
It also states that the parties to the conflict will set up a
joint military commission to carry out initial peacekeeping
operations until the deployment of the UN peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said Thursday that he did
not anticipate any problem for the official signing of the
agreement, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"All problems have been thrashed out... we don't expect any
issues that will delay the process further," said Chiluba, who has
been mediating the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire was due to have been signed in Lusaka on June
26, but was delayed by haggling over the details and the political
future of the vast central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
