<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Up, Wage Increase Down in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Employment in some major service
sectors of Hong Kong resumed growth on a year-on-year basis in
March 1999, while the increase in the wage index in nominal term
remained on a moderating trend.
</P>
<P>
According to the Census and Statistics Department Thursday, the
community, social and personal services sector had a larger
increase in employment, followed by the transport, storage and
communications sector.
</P>
<P>
But employment in the manufacturing sector and employment of
manual workers at construction sites continued to show marked
decrease.
</P>
<P>
Compared with December 1998, employment went up across almost
all the major sectors.
</P>
<P>
Vacancies, however, continued to decrease substantially both
across economic sectors and across occupation categories in March
1999 over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For all the sectors surveyed taken together, there were around
31,470 vacancies in March 1999, of which 25,040 were in the
private sector and 6,430 in the civil service.
</P>
<P>
Yet compared with December 1998, the picture was more
encouraging, with notable increases in vacancies seen for most of
the major economic sectors and occupation categories.
</P>
<P>
For all the major sectors surveyed taken together, the year-on-
year rate of increase in nominal terms declined from 5.2 percent
in March 1998 to 2.2 percent in September 1998, and further to 0.1
percent in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the companies surveyed reported no change
or a decrease in their average wage rates as compared to a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
After discounting the decrease in consumer prices, the wage
index for all the companies surveyed went up 2.6 percent in real
terms in March 1999 over a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
