ceremony although Sydney's Olympic organisers have offered a
compromise deal.
</P>
<P>
Organizing committee chief executive Sandy Hollway on Thursday
met with leaders of the school bands who are angry that initial
plans to have 1,500 foreign students perform at the opening
ceremony were shelved following a public backlash in Australia.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG president Michael Knight announced a compromise deal
earlier this week which would see the children perform at
prominent sites around Sydney during the games, including the
Opera House.
</P>
<P>
But Roy Anthony, the coordinator of the Southern California
school marching bands, says it is unlikely they will accept a
compromise and are considering legal action.
</P>
<P>
The band leaders released a statement ahead of Thursday's
meeting with Hollway, describing Knight as ``harsh and insensitive
'' for his decision.
</P>
<P>
Anthony said the children who were invited last September to
perform at the ceremony had been preparing ever since.
</P>
<P>
"The kids are going to have a hard time accepting that we've
abided by all (SOCOG'S) demands and all their wishes and yet they'
re saying no." Anthony told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 1,300 Americans and 200 Japanese marching band members
were booked to play at the opening ceremony. 
