<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Parliament Enacts Administrative Reform Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) on Thursday
passed two packages of administrative reform bills aimed at
restructuring the Japanese central government's ministries and
agencies and giving more power to local governments.
</P>
<P>
The bills, which cleared the House of Representatives (lower
house) in June, were approved overwhelmingly at a plenary session
of the House of Councilors, the upper house.
</P>
<P>
The reform laws will take effect in January 2001, while
decentralization laws would be enacted next April.
</P>
<P>
The reform package calls for streamlining the bureaucracy by
reorganizing the country's current 23 central government
institutions into 13 entities through mergers.
</P>
<P>
It is also aimed at strengthening the powers of the prime
minister and other senior government officials by transferring
some power over policy-making to local government authorities.
</P>
<P>
It calls for the establishment of an economic and fiscal policy
council headed by the prime minister to draw up basic policies on
budget formation and fiscal management, which currently fall under
the power of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, the number of Japan's central government
employees would be cut by 25 percent in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The decentralization package seeks to scrap the current
administrative system in order that the central government can
delegate administrative work to local governments and increase the
power of local authorities to adopt ordinances.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the merger of local authorities in order to
strengthen their administrative capabilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
