<HEADLINE> Russian PM to Visit Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin may go to Kosovo in a few weeks to present awards to the
200 paratroopers who rushed to the Slatina airport ahead of NATO
forces on June 12, the Interfax news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Stepashin is closely following the developments in Kosovo,"
and the visit does not at this point figure in Stepashin's
schedule for July, Interfax said, quoting government spokesman
Alexander Mikhailov.
</P>
<P>
However, Interfax, quoting sources in the Russian peacekeeping
assembly in Kosovo, said Stepashin and Airborne Troops Commander
Georgy Shpak are expected to arrive in Pristina, capital of the
Yugoslav province, at the end of the month, likely July 29 or 30.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, three warships with 182 Russian
peacekeepers, 13 armored carriers and 16 motor vehicles will sail
from the Black Sea port of Tuapse for the Balkans later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Two more ships are expected to depart on Friday in continued
deployment of the Russian contingent of 3,600 peacekeepers in
Kosovo, the Itar-Tass news agency reported. 
</P>
