<HEADLINE> Beijing Arts Festival for Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An arts festival to provide
entertainment and education for prisoners and juvenile delinquents
opened today in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
It will offer a series of literary and art activities with
singing contests, theatrical performances and literary exhibits in
prisons and reform schools. At today's opening ceremony there were
20 theater programs, 75 percent of which were the creations of
prisoners and prison officers.
</P>
<P>
It reflects a colorful aspect of prison life in Beijing and is
meant to help reform criminals and their aesthetics, according to
Wang Chongxun, the director of the Beijing Bureau of Prisons. He
explained that, after years of experience, they have learned that
a play, a song, or a poem can arouse a response in a criminal's
heart and cause him to live a new life.
</P>
<P>
One of the prisoners who was both a producer and performer
today, said that the opportunity to perform his own theatrical
programs in prison gave him confidence and a greater determination
to make a new man out of himself.
</P>
<P>
The festival is expected to run through September and the city'
s Bureau of Prisons plans to organize a singing group and
theatrical troupe after it finishes to tour prisons in Beijing and
they may even go public in future to gain more support from the
rest of society, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
