<HEADLINE> New Latvian President Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Vaira Vike-Freiberga was sworn in as
Latvia's new president Thursday in the Baltic state's parliament.
</P>
<P>
Vike-Freiberga, who spent decades in Canada before returning
to Latvia, is the first woman in Central and Eastern Europe to be
elected head of state.
</P>
<P>
She pledged to devote all her work "for the benefit of the
Latvian people" and to do everything possible "to ensure the well-
being of the Latvian state and population."
</P>
<P>
The new president also pledged "to honor and observe the
Latvian constitution and state law."
</P>
<P>
Vike-Freiberga, 61, replaces Guntis Ulmanis, who had been in
the office for six years.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Ulmanis will present Vike-Freiberga with the keys
to Riga Castle in a symbolic act of the handover of power, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Vike-Freiberga, a retired psychology professor, speaks French,
English, Spanish and German in addition to Latvian. She also
promised to begin learning Russian, the language of nearly 40
percent of the country's 2.5 million residents.
</P>
<P>
An inauguration ball will be staged in the evening in the
Rundales Palace. Ulmanis, other well-known Latvian politicians and
foreign representatives will be among the guests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
