<HEADLINE> Top Seed Kuerten Stumbles at Swiss Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil
stunned by American Vince Spadea, falling 6-2, 2-6, 7-6 in the
second round of the Swiss Open tennis tournament in Gstaad,
Switzerland, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 29th-ranked Spadea, who lost in the first round on grass at
Nottingham and Wimbledon, found that the return to clay brought a
return to form as he avenged a quarter-final loss to Kuerten at
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, the 1997 French Open champion and the winner of clay
court titles in Monte Carlo and Rome this season, lost the first
set without a fight.
</P>
<P>
When the players returned to the court after an hour's rain
delay early in the second set, the 22-year-old Brazilian seemed
finding his form as he won it 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten broke Spadea to open the third but the 24-year-old
American refused to fold and eventually forced the set to a
tiebreak which he won 8-6.
</P>
<P>
Spadea will play 1996 Swiss champion and eighth seed Albert
Costa of Spain, who came rallied to beat Austrian Stefan Koubek 6-
7, 6-1, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Mariano Zabaleta of Argentina won over Frenchman
Cedric Pioline 4-6, 6-3, 7-6 in the rain-delayed first-round game.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Felix Mantilla of Spain, the 1997 Swiss champion,
advanced into the second round with a 6-3, 6-2 victory over Franco
Squillari of Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
