<HEADLINE> Chinese World-Heritage Site Being Protected From Coal Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's Jiangxi Province plans to
spend 16 million yuan building a transformer substation next year
in the Lushan Mountain area to put an end to the pollution caused
by burning coal, at Jiujiang on the south bank of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
The 110-kv station is expected to make Lushan Mountain the
nation's first mountainous scenic spot that will be free from coal
smoke pollution.
</P>
<P>
Lushan Mountain is on UNESCO's world cultural heritage list but
has had a power supply problem for quite a long time and hotels
and people living there have to burn coal, but it is hoped that
the station will give everyone access to electricity.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province will transform the local low-voltage
electric power grids and reduce electricity fees locally to
encourage people to use electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
