<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serial Silkworm By-Products Developed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have developed
more than 30 kinds of drugs and cosmetics with natural compound
amino acid and other substances extracted from silkworm chrysalis
and excrement, including one drug that can be used to treat
aplastic anaemia.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted the achievements may help reduce the cost of
amino-acid-related products.
</P>
<P>
China produces four-fifths of the world's silk, with about 128,
000 tons of silkworm chrysalis and 400,000 tons of silkworm
excrement discarded each year.
</P>
<P>
Wei Kemin, a professor with the Zhejiang Research Institute of
Traditional Chinese Medicine, and his research team initiated
their study program on recycling of silk industry wastes at the
beginning of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
They successfully separated natural compound amino acid and
some other useful substances from the wastes.
</P>
<P>
The natural compound amino acid, which is much cheaper than
synthetic amino acid, contains 18 types of amino acid needed by
human bodies, according to Wei.
</P>
<P>
Wei estimated their research findings are likely to bring about
a new industry with an annual output value of some two billion
yuan when being popularized alone in Zhejiang Province, a major
silk producer which turns out about 30,000 tons of silkworm
chrysalis and 100,000 tons of silkworm excrement each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unprecedented Security Welcomes Sharif Back From U.S., U.K. Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The city of Lahore Thursday
witnessed unprecedented security as Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif returned from his visit to the United States, which evoked
strong criticism at home from the religion-political groups.
</P>
<P>
The special Police Elite Force and officials of the secret
agencies had sealed the Lahore airport and been monitoring all
roads leading to the airport to thwart any attempt of protest
rally before the prime minister's arrival at the capital of Punjab
province, informed sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Entry of the passengers and journalists was banned into the VIP
lounge one and a half hours before the plane carrying the prime
minister touched down. All main gates of the airport were closed
for passengers 30 minutes prior to the plane landing.
</P>
<P>
Sharif arrived at the airport aboard a Pakistani International
Airlines commercial plane at around 10:00 a.m. local time (0500
GMT) and then set out by air to Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
These tight security measures at the Lahore airport caused
great inconvenience to passengers, especially women, children and
the aged people, complained some common passengers, who had to
stand for one hour in scorching heat.
</P>
<P>
When the journalists asked why they were not allowed to enter
the VIP lounge, local police officer Cantt Khalid Sherdil, who had
full control of the security arrangements at the airport, said
that the prime minister had ordered not to allow any reporters to
come close to him.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Prime Minister's Implementation Commission
Rashid Warriach, however, did not agree with Sherdil, saying that
restriction on journalists is a conspiracy against the government.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton, Sharif
agreed to persuade the Kashmiri Mujahedeen (holy war fighters) to
withdraw from the peaks they occupy in the India-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The deal has aroused anger from most religious parties in
Pakistan and Kashmiri groups, who blamed Sharif for "selling out
the Kashmiris".
</P>
<P>
After the visit to the United States, Sharif went to London and
held talks with his British counterpart Tony Blair on the Kashmir
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
