<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Might Not Compete in Team Worlds Next Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Europe may not compete in the new
World Team Championship next season, soccer's continental
governing body UEFA said.
</P>
<P>
UEFA president Lennart Johansson said they had only grudgingly
agreed to the first ever tournament in Brazil in January, with the
six confederation winners plus two others to participate. But he
added UEFA could not guarantee the participation of a European
club in any subsequent event.
</P>
<P>
There had been a controversy around Manchester United's
decision to withdraw from FA Cup to play in the FIFA-organized,
eight-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
"We have to listen to our clubs. For this once, we are going
to Brazil out of loyalty to the football family but we cannot
guarantee participation in the future," Johansson was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Johansson, who attended a week-long FIFA meetings in Los
Angeles, said he however sympathized with the position of United.
</P>
<P>
But he denied that UEFA had already lined up Champions League
runners-up Bayern Munich instead of United because it would have
furthered the claims of Germany to be awarded the 2006 World Cup.
UEFA is backing Germany over England for the bid.
</P>
<P>
Johansson said he was "extremely disappointed" over United
decision. "We in UEFA were afraid something like this would
happen because of the overcrowded calendar," he said. "I don't
believe that the participation of either team would have had an
affect on the World Cup vote. What I do think is that we cannot,
in future, force our clubs to take part," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
