<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Carry out Projects for Rural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has planned to implement
thousands of projects for the development of the rural areas in
the new fiscal year, Al-Ahram daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Rural Development Mahmoud Al-Sherif
announced the plans on Wednesday at a press conference, during
which he said the projects are part of the Shrouk scheme aimed at
promoting Egypt's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,900 projects are to be carried out in the fiscal
year 1999-2000 starting on July 1 in the 26 governorates for
infrastructure construction and human development, Al-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
Facilities will be built relating to drinking water, roads,
electricity, bridges and sanitary drainage systems, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
As regards to human development, projects will be implemented
in the fields of education, health, child and mother care,
cultural centers and youth hostels in addition to small rural
development projects, Al-Sherif added.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 257.3 million Egyptian pounds
(75.68 million U.S. dollars) for the rural development plans,
including 30 million pounds (8.82 million dollars) for the
construction of new roads.
</P>
<P>
A growing disparity exists between Egypt's rural areas and
urban communities in infrastructures and wealth. The government
has in recent years been exerting efforts to improve the living
conditions in the sparsely-populated countryside through, among
other steps, the Shrouk plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
