<HEADLINE> Japanese Prime Minister Leaves Tokyo For Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
left here Thursday afternoon for Beijing on a three-day official
visit to China.
</P>
<P>
It is Obuchi's first visit to China since he took office last
July. During his visit, he will hold talks with Chinese leaders on
a wide-range of issues including economy and security.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Obuchi described his visit as a bridge
for the development of bilateral ties oriented toward the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi will explain to Chinese leaders the new Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation guidelines and express support for China's
early accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO), Japanese
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is accompanied by Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura,
Posts and Telecommunications Minister Seiko Noda and Home Affairs
Minister Takeshi Noda.
</P>
<P>
Japan's top business leaders including Shoichiro Toyoda,
honorary chairman of Toyota Motor Corp., also joined Obuchi on his
trip.
</P>
<P>
Before his leaving, he also met with nine Chinese students
studying in Japan at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi is scheduled to go to Mongolia on Saturday after ending
his visit to Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
