<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Province Saves Endangered Spring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The city of Dunhuang in China's
Gansu Province has spent nearly 5 million yuan saving a spring in
a desert area, that was drying up because of falling groundwater
levels in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
But now, the area around Yueya Spring, which is at the foot of
Mingsha Hill, has been increased from 0.17 ha. to 0.59 ha. and the
water level in the spring has risen to 1.09 meters from 40 cm
after 12,420 cu.m. of sand were removed.
</P>
<P>
It is still strange that the spring, which is surrounded by
sand dunes, has never been buried, nor has it dried up from a lack
of precipitation.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang, which is famous for its Mogao Grottoes, is one of the
world's leading collections of cave art, and Mingsha Hill, or
Singing Sands, and Yueya Spring are popular tourist attractions.
More than 400,000 tourists visit these sites each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
