<HEADLINE> Air Canada Reaches New Deal With Flight Attendants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada reached a deal at the mid-
night deadline with its 5,100 flight attendants on higher pensions
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the negotiators said under the deal flight
attendant at the age of 55 and after 25 years' service might be
paid a yearly pension of 19,200 Canadian dollars (about 13,056 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that Air Canada flight attendants usually
earn a maximum pension of about 22,000 Canadian dollars (about 14,
960 US dollars) a year after 35 years of service. They are paid 18,
000 (about 12,240 US dollars) to 38,500 Canadian dollars (26,180
US dollars) during their career.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the attendants said she was satisfied with
the "end results" of the negotiations, and the two sides would be
back for further discussions. Chief negotiators told a news
briefing that they were pleased business would return to normal.
</P>
<P>
The deal is to a relief of thousands of passengers trapped at
the country's airports, where they either managed to change planes
or sat through the negotiations in the hope of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
The progress is also a relief to many of the 7,000 athletes,
coaches and officials from across North and South America, who
could miss the Pan-American Games slated for July 23-August 8 if
Air Canada, the Games' official airline, is grounded.
</P>
<P>
The games will be the largest athletic event ever staged in
Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
