<HEADLINE> PC Shipments to Mideast to Reach 1 Million Units </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The total shipments of personal
computers (PCs) to the Middle East and North African markets are
estimated to hit an all-time high of 1 million units in 1999, a
local newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The largest markets for PCs in the region are Egypt, Saudi
Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE), which account for
two-thirds of all shipments, the Khaleej Times daily quoted
industry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The record-breaking 1 million units of total PC shipments will
represent an important milestone in the development of
information technology (IT) in the Middle East and North African
region, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the Middle East is the second fastest
growing market for IT in the world, after China. The IT market in
this region is estimated at 6.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1999,
compared to 4 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated the IT markets in Gulf countries will increase
to 2.3 billion dollars in 1999 from 1.48 billion dollars in
1997. The total PC market in Gulf countries is expected to reach
415,437 units this year from 266,104 units in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A number of factors have contributed to the growth of the PC
market in the Middle East, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
Notable among the factors is the boom in the development of
the Internet and e-commerce and expanding sales in the home
market and education sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990708.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankers Review Policies in Asia-Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Central bankers and policy makers
from the Asia-Pacific region gathered here Thursday in a regional
central banking conference to discuss regional central banking
policies as well as other economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Koh Yong Guan, managing director of the Monetary Authority of
Singapore, said in his opening address that the conference
provides an excellent opportunity to discuss some of the
challenges that central banks in the region face.
</P>
<P>
He questioned whether central banks should be concerned with
asset prices and how they cope with volatile capital flows during
this time of excessive stock market fluctuations and massive
capital flows.
</P>
<P>
Many central banks have relied on traditional monetary policy
operations, instead of imposing capital controls, to deal with
excessive flows, said Koh.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has highlighted the importance of sound regulation
and supervision of the financial sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
But how can central banks manage to regulate financial
institutions instead of stifling the growth of the financial
sector remains a tough job, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also asked those at the meeting to discuss the question
whether monetary policy is sufficient for macroeconomic stability.
</P>
<P>
"Prudent monetary policies can achieve low inflation but if
fiscal policies are too expansionary and labor markets are
inflexible, then price stability comes with high interest rates
and high unemployment", he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Nanyang Asia-Pacific Central Banking Conference,
organized by Nanyang Technological University, will last through
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
