<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PKK Leader Threatens More Attacks If not Spared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- In his latest message of plea and
threat, the convicted Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah
Ocalan warned again that if Turkey does not spare his life, his
PKK militants will escalate attacks on civilian and military
targets in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent out from his prison cell on Imrali Island in
Marmara Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa, Ocalan
warned he will lose control over the PKK rebels if Turkey does not
accept his "peace offer," the local Daily News reported here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Ocalan's lawyers as saying that Ocalan also
criticized Turkey in the letter for not taking steps toward
recognizing Kurdish rights.
</P>
<P>
In his three-page letter to the head of the prison, Ocalan
complained that little is being done to find a solution to the
Kurdish issue.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone speaks of problems of human rights, democracy and
economy," said Ocalan, "they don't even take tortoise steps toward
a solution, but they rush out to hang me."
</P>
<P>
Since he was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
February, Ocalan has repeatedly said that he will call on his
militants to lay down arms if his life is spared.
</P>
<P>
Despite the "life-for-peace" offer, the Ankara State Security
Court sentenced him to death on June 29 on charges of treason and
separatism.
</P>
<P>
Denying the charges, Ocalan, who led the PKK in its
15-years-old war for Kurdish independence which claimed 37,000
lives, said he had not killed anyone himself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
