<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Developments in Tibetology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China has made some progress in its
research on Tibet since the democratic reforms in the Tibet
Autonomous Region in 1959.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 research institutes, like China's Center of
Tibetology and the China Tibet Academy of Social Sciences, and
some 2,000 faculty members are engaged in Tibetology. They have
completed over 100 research projects and published more than 400
books and 40 different periodicals.
</P>
<P>
Before the democratic reforms of 1959, Tibet's cultural
heritage and relics were on the brink of extinction as artists and
Tibetologists were looked down upon by the local government, but
Tibetology has grown in the past 4 decades among academics in
China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Tibetology includes Tibetan linguistics and language, history,
philosophy, religion, literature, art, folklore, politics, the
economy, traditional Tibetan medicine, astronomy, geography,
handicrafts, and architecture.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of Karuo relics at Qamdo County that date back 5,
000 years and the Qugong relics from the northern suburb of Lhasa
that are 4,000 years old have provided valuable information for
Tibetology.
</P>
<P>
The popular Tibetan epic "Life of King Gesar," which was handed
down for generations orally by ballad singers, has been made a key
research project at a special institute that is collecting more
than 5,000 cassettes and several hundred video tapes on the epic.
</P>
<P>
This scattered oral tradition is being turned into a systematic,
monumental literary work for the first time and many Tibetan
scholars and Buddhists have acclaimed it as the realization of an
old wish of the Tibetan people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
